			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_icon?color=5d4037&amp;id=2000&amp;scale=400</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>4.01895141048376,6.455546218835619,16.41382754321085</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Irving oil refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Irving Oil Saint John Refinery
Classification: Mega-refinery
Location: Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada
Owner: Irving Oil, a privately owned Canadian refining and marketing company
Capacity: More than 320,000 barrels per day, making it Canada’s largest refinery
Main feedstocks: Imported Atlantic-basin crude, U.S. crude and some Canadian offshore crude, depending on economics and availability
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, heating oil, jet fuel, propane, asphalt and marine fuels
Markets: Eastern Canada and especially the northeastern United States; more than half of its finished products are exported to the U.S. market
Recent data: Irving Oil announced a C$100 million modernization of the refinery’s fluid catalytic cracking unit, aimed at improving reliability and long-term competitiveness
Strategic role: Major fuel supplier to Atlantic Canada and New England, supported by the nearby Canaport deep-water terminal for crude imports and product exports
Risks: Dependence on imported crude, Atlantic weather, refinery outages, U.S.–Canada trade measures, volatile refining margins and marine-logistics disruptions</description>
