		<Placemark id="00E0A67AB93F337E4686">
			<name>PetroChina Dalian Petrochemical Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: PetroChina Dalian Petrochemical Refinery
Classification: Former mega-refinery / currently idled
Location: Dalian, Liaoning Province, China
Owner: PetroChina, controlled by China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC)
Historical capacity: About 410,000 barrels per day, or roughly 20.5 million tonnes per year
Main feedstocks: Historically Russian ESPO crude and other imported or domestic crude grades
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, naphtha, LPG, marine fuels and petrochemical feedstocks
Markets: Mainly northeastern China, with access to regional Asian markets through Dalian’s port infrastructure
Recent data: PetroChina shut the refinery in 2025 as part of a relocation and modernization strategy. A possible restart of one 200,000 b/d crude unit was considered for 2026 to process discounted Russian oil, but the restart was later delayed.
Replacement project: PetroChina approved a new refining and petrochemical complex on Changxing Island, including a refinery of about 200,000 b/d and a large ethylene unit.
Strategic role: Historically one of northern China’s largest refineries and an important processor of Russian Far East crude
Risks: Permanent closure or delayed restart, regulatory uncertainty, sanctions affecting Russian crude, weak Chinese fuel demand, refining overcapacity and port disruption</description>
