		<Placemark id="0139C43BD53EAF130578">
			<name>Aster Bukom Refinery &amp; Petrochemical Complex</name>
			<description>Site: Aster Bukom Refinery &amp; Petrochemical Complex
Classification: Large integrated refinery and petrochemical complex; planned expansion above the mega-refinery threshold
Location: Pulau Bukom, Singapore
Owner: Aster Chemicals and Energy, owned through the Chandra Asri–Glencore joint venture; Shell completed the sale in April 2025.
Current capacity: Approximately 237,000 b/d of refining capacity, plus a 1.1 million t/year ethylene cracker.
Planned capacity: Around 307,000 b/d after activation of a 70,000 b/d condensate splitter, expected in the second half of 2026.
Main feedstocks: Imported crude oil, condensate and naphtha
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, naphtha, LPG, marine fuels, base oils and petrochemical feedstocks
Markets: Singapore and export markets throughout Southeast and Northeast Asia
Recent data: Aster is investing about US$155 million to modernise the refinery, increase capacity and improve product value.
Strategic role: Major integrated refining, chemicals and trading hub beside the Singapore Strait
Risks: Imported-feedstock dependence, Malacca and Singapore Strait congestion, unit outages, carbon costs and weak Asian petrochemical margins</description>
