		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="00704926E43F39FE1427">
			<name>Midland Refineries Company – Najaf Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Midland Refineries Company – Najaf Refinery
Classification: Small conventional refinery / major expansion project
Location: Najaf Governorate, central-southern Iraq
Owner/Operator: Midland Refineries Company (MRC), a state-owned company under the Iraqi Ministry of Oil
Current capacity: Approximately 30,000 barrels per day
Planned capacity: 100,000 barrels per day, through the addition of a new 70,000 b/d refining unit. Expansion works were launched in 2025, with Iraqi authorities targeting completion within roughly one year, although the actual commissioning schedule may change.
Main feedstocks: Iraqi crude oil supplied through the national pipeline and storage network
Main products: Gasoline, diesel/gas oil, kerosene, fuel oil and other petroleum products
Reported production: Around 825,000 litres/day of gasoline, 650,000 litres/day of kerosene, 650,000 litres/day of gas oil, and approximately 6 million litres/day of fuel oil for power stations in Najaf and Karbala.
Markets: Primarily Najaf Governorate, Karbala and surrounding areas of central Iraq
Strategic role: Supports regional fuel supply and forms part of Iraq’s broader strategy to reduce petroleum-product imports and increase domestic refining capacity
Risks: Expansion delays, ageing existing units, power interruptions, pipeline dependence, construction overruns and differences between nominal capacity and actual throughput</description>
