		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0DEF63193A3F60C0D278">
			<name>Raffinerie de Lavéra</name>
			<description>Refinery: Petroineos Lavéra Refinery
Classification: Large integrated refinery–petrochemical complex, not a mega-refinery
Location: Lavéra industrial area, Martigues, Bouches-du-Rhône, near Marseille, France postal code 13117
Owner/Operator: Petroineos Manufacturing France SAS, part of the Petroineos refining and trading joint venture between INEOS and PetroChina
Capacity: Approximately 210,000 barrels per day, equivalent to around 10 million tonnes of crude oil per year.
Main feedstocks: Imported crude oils received by tanker through Lavéra’s Mediterranean marine-terminal and jetty infrastructure.
Main products: LPG, naphtha, gasoline, diesel, heating oil, marine gasoil, Jet A-1 aviation fuel, high- and low-sulfur fuel oils, bunker fuels and several grades of paving and industrial bitumen.
Markets: Southern and southeastern France, local airports, the Rhône Valley and Alpine regions, Switzerland, southern Germany and international Mediterranean markets. Products are distributed through the SPMR and NATO pipeline systems as well as by ship, river, rail and road.
Configuration: Highly integrated coastal refinery–petrochemical complex with extensive crude-import and product-export jetties, large storage infrastructure, pipeline connections and downstream petrochemical units producing olefins, aromatics, polymers and chemical intermediates.
Recent development: In April 2024, INEOS completed the acquisition of TotalEnergies’ interests in several adjacent Lavéra petrochemical assets, including the Naphtachimie steam cracker, the Appryl polypropylene business, the Gexaro aromatics business and associated naphtha storage, strengthening integration across the wider industrial complex.
Strategic role: The largest refinery in southern France, one of the largest refining sites in southern Europe and a major regional producer of transport fuels, aviation fuel, marine fuels and bitumen. Following the end of crude refining at Grangemouth in April 2025, Lavéra became Petroineos’ principal operating crude-refining asset.
Risks: Mediterranean crude-import or maritime disruption, refinery and petrochemical-unit outages, dependence on integrated downstream chemical facilities, pipeline interruptions, labour action, fires, emissions restrictions, high European energy and carbon costs and declining demand for conventional road and marine fuels.</description>
