		<Placemark id="020D85F33C3F60C57D88">
			<name>TotalEnergies Plateforme de Feyzin - Zone A Bitume</name>
			<description>Refinery: TotalEnergies Feyzin Refining and Petrochemical Platform
Classification: Medium-sized integrated refinery–petrochemical platform not a mega-refinery
Location: Avenue Jean-Jaurès, Feyzin, Rhône, south of Lyon, France postal code 69320
Owner/Operator: TotalEnergies Raffinage France
Capacity: Approximately 119,000 barrels per day; the platform processes close to 5 million tonnes of crude oil annually.
Main feedstocks: Imported crude oils delivered by pipeline from the Fos-sur-Mer Mediterranean oil terminals through the SPSE system and the Saint-Quentin-Fallavier crude-storage facility.
Main products: Gasoline, jet fuel, diesel, heating oil, heavy fuel oil, LPG, bitumen and petrochemical intermediates including ethylene, propylene, butadiene and aromatics.
Markets: Primarily the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region and wider eastern France. The platform produces more than 55% of the fuels consumed in the Rhône-Alpes region and supplies petrochemical customers through its pipeline network.
Configuration: Integrated inland refining and petrochemical complex combining fuel-production units, a steam cracker, bitumen facilities, crude and product storage sites and more than 1,000 kilometres of pipelines. Products can be distributed by pipeline, rail, road and barge.
Recent development: TotalEnergies reports that nearly €550 million has been invested in the platform over a ten-year period to improve safety, product quality, operational performance and market adaptability, including more than €150 million dedicated to reducing its environmental impact.
Strategic role: One of TotalEnergies’ three operating crude-oil refineries in metropolitan France and a major fuel and petrochemical supplier for southeastern and eastern France.
Risks: Dependence on the Fos-sur-Mer–Feyzin crude-pipeline system, refinery and petrochemical-unit outages, pipeline disruptions, labour action, fires or explosions, environmental restrictions, high European energy and carbon costs and declining regional demand for conventional road fuels.</description>
