		<Placemark id="026F5C12253F7F2E7513">
			<name>Port-Jérôme-Gravenchon Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Port-Jérôme–Gravenchon Refinery
Classification: Large refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Port-Jérôme-sur-Seine, near Le Havre, Normandy, France
Current owner/operator: North Atlantic Energies, controlled by North Atlantic France
Former owner/operator: Esso S.A.F. / ExxonMobil
Capacity: Approximately 230,000 barrels per day of crude oil and other feedstocks. Some older sources cite around 240,000–270,000 b/d, depending on the perimeter and methodology used.
Main feedstocks: Imported crude oils and intermediate feedstocks supplied through the lower-Seine maritime, terminal and pipeline network
Main products: Gasoline, diesel/gasoil, jet fuel, LPG, heating oil, heavy fuel oil, lubricating base oils and specialty petroleum products
Markets: France, particularly Normandy and the Paris region, with access to Northwest European markets
Integration: Large integrated refining, lubricants and petrochemical platform with two crude-distillation trains and several conversion units
Recent ownership change: North Atlantic completed the acquisition of ExxonMobil’s controlling interest in Esso S.A.F. in November 2025. Esso S.A.F. was subsequently renamed North Atlantic Energies.
Strategic role: France’s second-largest refinery and an important supplier of transport fuels and base oils. North Atlantic Energies represents about 20% of French refining capacity.
Risks: Refinery fires, Seine and Le Havre logistics disruption, ageing equipment, labour action, high European energy and carbon costs, weak refining margins and transition-related investment requirements</description>
