		<Placemark id="0539CC89753FA08F8DA4">
			<name>BP Gelsenkirchen refinery complex</name>
			<description>Refinery: BP Gelsenkirchen Refinery Complex
Classification: Large refinery — not a mega-refinery under its reduced configuration
Location: Gelsenkirchen, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany
Current owner: BP Europa SE / Ruhr Oel GmbH
Agreed buyer: Klesch Group; completion is expected in the second half of 2026, subject to regulatory approval
Capacity: Historically about 265,000 b/d or 12 million tonnes per year; BP previously announced a reduction toward roughly 8 million tonnes per year, equivalent to about 175,000–180,000 b/d
Main feedstocks: Imported crude delivered through Northwest European pipeline and terminal networks
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, heating oil, LPG and petrochemical feedstocks such as ethylene and propylene
Markets: Mainly Germany and the Rhine-Ruhr industrial region, including road transport, aviation and petrochemical customers
Recent data: In March 2026, BP agreed to sell the refinery to Klesch Group. The complex employs about 1,800 people, and the transaction remains subject to government and regulatory approvals.
Strategic role: One of Germany’s largest integrated refining and petrochemical sites, serving the densely populated and industrialized Ruhr region
Risks: Ownership-transition uncertainty, European refining overcapacity, high energy and carbon costs, refinery-unit closures, pipeline-supply disruption and declining regional fuel demand</description>
