		<Placemark>
			<name>Valero Jean-Gaulin Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Valero Jean-Gaulin Refinery
Classification: Large refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Lévis, near Québec City, Quebec, Canada
Owner/Operator: Valero Energy
Throughput capacity: Approximately 235,000 barrels per day according to Valero. Some Canadian regulatory sources cite a higher nominal capacity of about 265,000 b/d, so 235,000 b/d is the most suitable operational figure for your map.
Main feedstocks: Primarily imported and Canadian sweet crude oils, delivered through the refinery’s marine terminal and eastern Canadian logistics network
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, home-heating oil, butane and low-sulfur fuel oil.
Markets: Quebec and other eastern Canadian markets, supplied through Valero’s associated terminals, pipelines and wholesale network
Logistics: The refinery is located on the south shore of the St. Lawrence River and benefits from direct marine access, product terminals and pipeline connections
Strategic role: One of Quebec’s two operating refineries and a major supplier of transportation and heating fuels to eastern Canada. Valero states that its Canadian network supplies a substantial share of Quebec’s petroleum-product demand.
Risks: St. Lawrence marine disruption, severe winter weather, refinery-unit outages, maintenance shutdowns, crude-import dependence, environmental regulation and eastern Canadian fuel-demand exposure</description>
