		<Placemark>
			<name>Imperial Oil Sarnia Refinery</name>
			<description>Imperial Oil Sarnia Refinery
Classification: Conventional refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Sarnia, Ontario, Canada, within the Sarnia–Lambton “Chemical Valley” industrial cluster
Owner/Operator: Imperial Oil Limited, majority-owned by ExxonMobil
Capacity: Approximately 119,000–124,000 barrels per day. The refinery processed about 113,000 b/d in 2025.
Main feedstocks: Mainly Canadian crude oil, including western Canadian conventional and synthetic crude supplied through the regional pipeline network
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, aviation fuel, home-heating oil, marine fuel, naphtha and petrochemical feedstocks.
Markets: Ontario, the Great Lakes region and other eastern Canadian markets
Integration: The refinery is integrated with Imperial’s adjacent chemical plant, which produces polyethylene, solvents, aromatics, higher olefins and other petrochemical products.
Recent data: The site underwent planned turnaround and maintenance work during 2025. Imperial reported company-wide refinery throughput of about 402,000 b/d and utilization of 93% for the full year, although those figures cover all three Imperial refineries rather than Sarnia alone.
Strategic role: A major integrated refining, petrochemical and petroleum-research site serving eastern Canada
Risks: Enbridge Line 5 or other pipeline disruption, Great Lakes logistics constraints, refinery and chemical-unit outages, high maintenance requirements, environmental regulation and exposure to Canadian fuel-demand trends</description>
