		<Placemark id="0A1B1F07B940677889E3">
			<name>Amreya Petroleum Refining Company — APRC</name>
			<description>Refinery: Amreya Petroleum Refining Company — APRC
Classification: Conventional refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Amreya industrial area, west of Alexandria, Egypt
Owner/Operator: Amreya Petroleum Refining Company, wholly owned by the Egyptian General Petroleum Corporation (EGPC)
Capacity: Approximately 81,000 barrels per day, or around 3.8 million tonnes of crude oil per year.
Main feedstocks: Egyptian and imported crude oils supplied through Alexandria’s petroleum infrastructure
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, LPG/butane, lubricating base oils, waxes, alkyl benzene, aromatics and other petroleum intermediates
Markets: Mainly Egypt’s domestic market, with selected exports of waxes, distillates and specialty petroleum products
Configuration: Primarily a hydroskimming refinery, supplemented by reforming, aromatics, lubricant and wax-processing units
Recent production: APRC reported production of approximately 3 million tonnes of petroleum products in FY 2024/25, while supplying about 1.1 million tonnes of feedstocks to other Egyptian petroleum companies.
Recent development: More than EGP 2 billion of projects were announced in 2025, including the restart of a 5,000 m³/hour hydrogen unit and an upgrade expected to add roughly 100,000 tonnes per year of gasoline production.
Strategic role: An important part of the Alexandria refining cluster, producing transport fuels as well as higher-value lubricants, waxes and aromatic products
Risks: Ageing infrastructure, relatively low conversion complexity, refinery outages, high energy consumption, fire hazards and dependence on Alexandria’s crude-supply and logistics network</description>
