	<Folder>
		<name>Major Oil Storage &amp; Distribution Terminals</name>
		<Placemark id="ADDGOR00000000000001">
			<name>Rostock Oil Harbour &amp; GÖR Tank Farm (Euroports)</name>
			<description><![CDATA[Terminal: Rostock Oil Harbour &amp; GÖR Tank Farm (Großtanklager-Ölhafen Rostock)<br>Classification: Baltic crude and products import terminal — head of the Rostock–Schwedt pipeline (MVL)<br>Location: Peez, Port of Rostock, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Germany<br>Owner/Operator: Großtanklager-Ölhafen Rostock GmbH (GÖR), subsidiary of Euroports Germany — sole owner since acquiring Total Deutschland's stake in the former joint venture; GÖR also operates the on-site tanks of PCK Raffinerie Schwedt and Dow Olefinverbund Böhlen; PCK owns its own crude tank farm and a dedicated pier<br>Infrastructure: Six tanker berths for vessels up to 100,000 tonnes, discharge capacity up to 6,000 tonnes per hour; ~700,000 m³ of storage; rail loading (7 tracks), automated truck loading; on-site biodiesel plant (~200,000 t/y)<br>Handles: Crude oil, mineral oil products, heavy fuel oil, VGO, biodiesel, HVO, methanol, ethanol, vegetable oils<br>Connectivity: Crude pipeline to the PCK Schwedt refinery (MVL, ~200 km) and product pipeline to Böhlen (Dow); rail and road distribution across eastern Germany<br>Recent data: Around 6 million tonnes of crude per year pumped from tankers into the Schwedt pipeline since Germany ended Russian pipeline imports — securing fuel supply for eastern Germany and Berlin<br>Strategic role: The seaborne entry point that replaced Druzhba for the Schwedt refinery; the first link of the chain tanker → GÖR → MVL → Schwedt → Berlin fuel market<br>Risks: Berth size limit (~100,000 t — Aframax scale, no larger); throughput bottleneck relative to Schwedt's nameplate capacity; Baltic weather and single-corridor dependence]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_red-circle1</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>12.14519945455248,54.14954764676539,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="ADDDAL00000000000001">
			<name>Dalmeny Tank Farm (FPS)</name>
			<description><![CDATA[Terminal: Dalmeny Tank Farm (FPS crude storage)<br>Classification: Crude oil storage — the buffer between the Forties Pipeline System and the Hound Point export jetty<br>Location: Dalmeny, South Queensferry, Firth of Forth, Scotland<br>Owner/Operator: INEOS FPS<br>Infrastructure: Six floating-roof tanks, ~3 million barrels of storage; fed from Kinneil (Grangemouth) by a 19 km, 30-inch line; connected to Hound Point by 48-inch and 40-inch loading lines (~5 km)<br>Handles: Stabilised Forties Blend crude<br>Strategic role: Decouples continuous pipeline flow from batch tanker liftings — the pipeline never stops, ships load on schedule<br>Risks: Modest storage relative to system throughput (~3 million barrels against flows of several hundred thousand b/d) — limited slack if liftings are delayed]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_red-circle0</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-3.38,55.99,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="ADDHPT00000000000001">
			<name>Hound Point Marine Terminal</name>
			<description><![CDATA[Terminal: Hound Point Marine Terminal<br>Classification: Deep-water crude export terminal — the loading point of Forties Blend<br>Location: Firth of Forth, ~3 km east of the Forth Bridge, near Edinburgh, Scotland<br>Owner/Operator: INEOS FPS (within the Forth Ports Authority area); opened 1975<br>Infrastructure: Offshore island structure with two deep-water jetties and a vapour recovery platform; loading up to 8,000 m³/hour per berth; dedicated escort tug fleet<br>Vessels: Berths accommodate tankers up to ~350,000 dwt — one of the few UK terminals able to load VLCCs; roughly 200 vessels per year<br>Handles: Forties Blend (typically ~38–41° API, ~0.6–0.8% sulphur) — a Dated Brent benchmark grade<br>Strategic role: The exact point where the Forties chain on this map goes from pipeline to ship — wellhead → FPS → Kinneil → Dalmeny → Hound Point → Rotterdam<br>Risks: Benchmark sensitivity — outages here feed directly into Dated Brent assessments; weather and tidal constraints in the Firth]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_red-circle0</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-3.359,56.005,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="ADDSIOT0000000000001">
			<name>SIOT Trieste Marine Terminal</name>
			<description><![CDATA[Terminal: SIOT Trieste Marine Terminal (Società Italiana per l'Oleodotto Transalpino)<br>Classification: Crude import terminal — head of the TAL pipeline system<br>Location: Bay of Muggia, Port of Trieste, Italy<br>Owner/Operator: SIOT / TAL Group (shareholders include OMV, Shell, Eni, ExxonMobil, MERO ČR, Gunvor, TotalEnergies, Phillips 66 and Rosneft)<br>Infrastructure: Marine piers with tanker berths — first Suezmax berthed in May 2025 after the Fincantieri revamp — plus a tank farm feeding the TAL pipeline<br>Capacity: ~37 million tonnes of crude received per year (~400 tankers annually)<br>Connectivity: Sea-side entry of the entire Alpine corridor — TAL to Bavaria (Bayernoil, Gunvor Ingolstadt), Karlsruhe (MiRO), Austria (AWP branch) and the Czech Republic (via IKL)<br>Strategic role: The single most important crude gateway for landlocked Central Europe; the physical starting point of the Czech Republic's post-Russia supply route<br>Risks: Corridor concentration — an outage at Trieste ripples into refineries in four countries; Adriatic weather and port constraints]]></description>
