		<Placemark id="0E3910379A3EAF1571E4">
			<name>Pulau Bukom Oil Storage &amp; Marine Terminal</name>
			<description>Terminal: Pulau Bukom Oil Storage &amp; Marine Terminal
Classification: Major crude-import, storage and refined-product export terminal
Location: Western section of Pulau Bukom, Singapore
Owner/Operator: Aster Chemicals and Energy
Infrastructure: 13 marine jetties—12 at Pulau Bukom Besar and one at Pulau Ular—plus a Single Buoy Mooring.
Main activity: Crude oil is imported primarily through the offshore buoy; refined products are moved by submarine pipelines and loaded onto vessels at the terminal jetties.
Typical vessels: Product tankers, Aframax and Suezmax vessels; upgraded offshore infrastructure is intended to accommodate VLCC cargoes of up to about 2 million barrels.
Strategic role: Supplies feedstock to the Bukom refinery and exports fuels and petrochemical products into the Asian trading market
Recent data: Aster is upgrading the offshore buoy and related berth infrastructure to reduce crude-import costs and increase operational flexibility.
Risks: Strait congestion, marine collision, oil spills, berth outages, severe thunderstorms and disruption to regional shipping lanes</description>
