		<Placemark>
			<name>Westridge Marine Terminal</name>
			<description>Terminal: Westridge Marine Terminal
Classification: Major crude-oil export terminal / Pacific gateway
Location: Burnaby, British Columbia, within the Port of Vancouver, Canada
Owner/Operator: Trans Mountain Corporation, a Canadian federal Crown corporation
Main commodities: Primarily western Canadian crude oil, including light, synthetic and heavy crude blends; the terminal also handles aviation-fuel movements serving Vancouver International Airport
Export capacity: Up to approximately 630,000 barrels per day through the marine terminal. The wider Trans Mountain pipeline system has a nominal capacity of about 890,000 b/d following completion of the expansion project in May 2024.
Marine infrastructure: Three tanker berths capable of handling Aframax-class tankers
Typical cargo size: Aframax vessels normally carry around 550,000–725,000 barrels, but draft restrictions through Vancouver Harbour’s Second Narrows generally limit loading to about 75–80% of full capacity.
Expected vessel traffic: Up to approximately 34 Aframax tankers and three barges per month at full utilization
Connected infrastructure: Direct terminus of the Trans Mountain pipeline system, linking Alberta’s oil-producing regions with the Pacific coast
Main export markets: Asia-Pacific markets, particularly China, California and other Pacific destinations, alongside western Canadian domestic markets
Recent development: The Trans Mountain Expansion Project increased pipeline capacity from 300,000 b/d to 890,000 b/d and transformed Westridge from a single-berth facility into a three-berth export complex.
Strategic role: Canada’s principal Pacific crude-export terminal, providing western Canadian producers with direct access to overseas markets and reducing dependence on exports to the United States
Risks: Oil-spill risk in Burrard Inlet and the Salish Sea, tanker restrictions through Second Narrows, pipeline outages, Indigenous and environmental opposition, marine congestion, earthquakes, wildfire-related disruption and exposure to heavy-crude export demand</description>
