		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Trans Mountain Burnaby Crude Oil Storage &amp; Distribution Terminal</name>
			<description>Terminal: Trans Mountain Burnaby Terminal
Classification: Major inland crude-oil and refined-products storage and distribution terminal
Location: Burnaby, British Columbia, Canada, on the southern slope of Burnaby Mountain
Owner/Operator: Trans Mountain Corporation
Main commodities: Western Canadian crude oil, including light, synthetic and heavy crude blends, diluted bitumen, and selected refined petroleum products
Storage capacity: Approximately 5.5 million barrels across 26 storage tanks.
Connected infrastructure: Final inland terminal of the Trans Mountain Pipeline System, connected to the Parkland Burnaby Refinery, local product terminals and the Westridge Marine Terminal through pipeline infrastructure, including the underground connection toward Westridge
Pipeline-system capacity: The expanded Trans Mountain system has a nominal capacity of approximately 890,000 barrels per day, compared with about 300,000 b/d before the expansion entered service in May 2024.
Main functions: Receipt, temporary storage, segregation, blending and redistribution of crude oil and refined products
Marine role: The Burnaby Terminal itself does not load export tankers. Crude intended for seaborne export is transferred onward to the nearby Westridge Marine Terminal
Main destinations: Westridge Marine Terminal, Parkland Burnaby Refinery, regional British Columbia fuel terminals and, through the wider pipeline system, refineries in Washington State
Safety infrastructure: Full-service fire protection, emergency-response equipment, stormwater treatment, vapour and odour-control systems, and continuous monitoring
Strategic role: Key balancing and distribution hub at the Pacific end of the Trans Mountain network, linking Alberta crude production with local refining, regional fuel distribution and overseas exports through Westridge
Risks: Tank fires, crude spills, pipeline interruption, seismic risk, wildfire exposure, vapour emissions, community opposition and congestion within the terminal-to-marine transfer system</description>
