		<Placemark id="097BFD27603F2360CAA1">
			<name>Sheskharis Oil Terminal</name>
			<description>Terminal: Sheskharis Oil Terminal
Classification: Major crude-oil export terminal / strategic Black Sea hub
Location: Tsemes Bay, Port of Novorossiysk, Krasnodar Krai, Russia
Owner/Operator: Operated within the Transneft system, principally through Chernomortransneft
Main commodities: Russian crude oil, diesel, fuel oil, naphtha and other refined petroleum products
Estimated loading volume: Approximately 700,000 barrels per day of crude oil under normal recent operating conditions; volumes can vary substantially according to export schedules and disruptions.
Storage infrastructure: Integrated with the inland Grushovaya Balka tank farm, forming a combined storage and transshipment complex with more than 1 million m³ of oil and petroleum-product storage capacity
Berths / vessel size: Multiple tanker berths; the largest deep-water berth can accommodate crude tankers of up to roughly 250,000 DWT and about 19 m draft, allowing the handling of large Suezmax vessels and some VLCC-scale cargo operations
Connected infrastructure: Southern outlet of Russia’s Transneft crude-pipeline system, connected by pipeline and tunnel infrastructure to the Grushovaya storage depot
Main export markets: Mediterranean, Turkey, Asia and other international markets reached through the Black Sea and Turkish Straits
Strategic role: One of Russia’s most important Black Sea oil-export facilities and a major outlet for crude from the national pipeline network. Disruptions at Novorossiysk can affect a significant share of Russian seaborne exports and influence international oil prices.
Recent developments: The terminal suffered repeated Ukrainian drone and missile attacks during 2025 and 2026. Some strikes temporarily suspended loading operations and damaged berths, storage or associated infrastructure, although exports were subsequently restarted after several interruptions.
Risks: Drone and missile attacks, temporary port closures, damage to tanks and loading arms, Black Sea security risks, Turkish Straits congestion, sanctions, adverse weather and pipeline interruptions</description>
