		<Placemark id="0AA59C3CB23F2D0D4068">
			<name>BOTAŞ Ceyhan Oil Terminal</name>
			<description>Terminal: BOTAŞ Ceyhan Oil Terminal
Alternative name: Ceyhan Marine Terminal / Kirkuk–Ceyhan Terminal
Classification: Major crude-oil export and storage terminal
Location: Ceyhan, Adana Province, Mediterranean coast of Türkiye
Owner/Operator: BOTAŞ — Petroleum Pipeline Corporation
Main commodities: Primarily Iraqi crude oil transported through the Iraq–Türkiye pipeline; the terminal can also support storage, blending and onward crude transportation within Türkiye
Pipeline capacity: The Iraq–Türkiye system consists of parallel 40-inch and 46-inch pipelines, with a stated annual capacity of 70.9 million tonnes, broadly equivalent to around 1.4–1.5 million barrels per day.
Storage capacity: Historically 12 crude tanks of 850,000 barrels each, giving about 10.2 million barrels. BOTAŞ reported in April 2026 that current Ceyhan storage capacity was approximately 11 million barrels, with a planned expansion to 45 million barrels.
Berths: A 1,950-metre marine jetty capable of loading up to four tankers simultaneously.
Connected infrastructure: Iraq–Türkiye crude pipeline, Ceyhan–Kırıkkale pipeline, regional storage systems and the wider Ceyhan energy hub
Main export markets: Mediterranean Europe and other international markets reached through the Mediterranean, Suez Canal and Gibraltar
Recent operations: Iraqi crude exports through the route resumed after a prolonged interruption, but current flows remain well below the pipeline’s nominal capacity. Türkiye and Iraq were negotiating a temporary extension of their pipeline agreement in July 2026.
Strategic role: Türkiye’s principal terminal for Iraqi crude and a major alternative export outlet for Iraq, reducing dependence on Persian Gulf routes
Risks: Iraq–Türkiye political and contractual disputes, pipeline sabotage, regional security instability, earthquakes, marine-loading interruptions, underutilization and crude-supply disruptions</description>
