		<Placemark id="0AC4204AAF3F2D0EA8F4">
			<name>BTC (Baku–Tbilisi–Ceyhan) Terminal</name>
			<description>Terminal: BTC Ceyhan Marine Terminal — Baku–Tbilisi–Ceyhan
Alternative name: Haydar Aliyev Marine Terminal
Classification: Major crude-oil export terminal / Caspian–Mediterranean gateway
Location: Ceyhan, Adana Province, Mediterranean coast of Türkiye
Owner: BTC Co., the international consortium owning the Baku–Tbilisi–Ceyhan pipeline and terminal
Operator: Operational control of the BTC system transferred from BP to SOCAR on 1 July 2026; BP remains a major shareholder in the consortium.
Main commodities: Primarily Azeri Light crude from the Azeri–Chirag–Gunashli fields, Shah Deniz condensate and selected Kazakh crude volumes transported across the Caspian Sea to Azerbaijan
Pipeline capacity: More than 1 million barrels per day through the approximately 1,767 km BTC pipeline, running from the Sangachal Terminal near Baku through Georgia to Ceyhan.
Storage capacity: Seven floating-roof crude tanks, each holding approximately 1 million barrels, giving total storage of around 7 million barrels or 1.06 million m³.
Berths / vessel size: Two tanker berths on an approximately 2.5 km offshore jetty, capable of loading vessels of up to about 300,000 DWT; the installation can accommodate very large crude carriers and load two tankers simultaneously.
Connected infrastructure: Direct terminus of the BTC crude pipeline, linked upstream to the Sangachal oil and gas processing terminal in Azerbaijan
Main export markets: Mediterranean Europe, Northwest Europe and international markets accessible through the Suez Canal and Gibraltar
Recent operations: BTC exports were temporarily disrupted in July 2025 after organic-chloride contamination affected some Azeri crude cargoes. Loadings continued after enhanced testing, while off-specification crude was segregated in terminal storage tanks.
Strategic role: Provides Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan with a major export route that bypasses Russia and the Turkish Straits, connecting Caspian production directly to the Mediterranean market
Risks: Pipeline sabotage or security incidents, earthquakes and landslides, crude-quality contamination, marine-loading interruptions, regional geopolitical tension, wildfires, severe weather and temporary reductions in upstream production</description>
