		<Placemark>
			<name>Bonny terminal tank farm</name>
			<description>Official name: Bonny Terminal (Shell Bonny Oil &amp; Gas Terminal)
Asset type: Onshore crude oil storage tank farm and terminal facility
Country: Nigeria
Region: Rivers State, Niger Delta
Nearest settlement: Bonny Island / Finima
Latitude / Longitude: 4.42°N, 7.16°E
Coordinate confidence: Representative (two independent port-registry sources agree within ~2 km)
Operator: Shell Petroleum Development Company (SPDC), now Renaissance Africa Energy as of March 2025, operating on behalf of the NNPC joint venture
Rated throughput: ~250,000 b/d
Storage capacity: ~5.7 million barrels (per NUPRC&apos;s crude terminal register)
Role in the supply chain: This is where crude arriving from the two feeder pipeline systems — the Trans Niger Pipeline (from Bomu/Ogoniland via the Rumuekpe hub) and the Nembe Creek Trunk Line (from the Nembe/OML 29 area via Cawthorne Channel) — is received, commingled and held in tankage before export. It has no built harbour or quay; it is purely a shore-based reception and storage facility. Crude leaves it by submarine pipeline to the offshore loading point.
Source: NUPRC crude oil terminal operations register; port-registry coordinate cross-check (portcode.net / SeaRates)</description>
