	<Folder>
		<name>Ports &amp; Maritime Logistics Hubs</name>
		<Placemark id="0D87D3F4054051EE7A6E">
			<name>Port of Fujairah – Oil Trading, Storage &amp; Bunkering Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: Port of Fujairah – Oil Trading, Storage &amp; Bunkering Hub
Classification: Global oil-storage, trading, blending, bunkering and crude-export hub
Location: Emirate of Fujairah, United Arab Emirates, on the Gulf of Oman and outside the Strait of Hormuz
Owner/Operator: Port of Fujairah; individual storage terminals are operated by international and regional companies, while ADNOC operates separate crude-export infrastructure connected to the port.
Main commodities: Crude oil, fuel oil, diesel, gasoil, jet fuel, gasoline, naphtha, marine fuels, LPG, bitumen, base oils and chemical products
Main facilities: Fujairah Oil Tanker Terminals, the Fujairah Oil Industry Zone, independent tank farms, crude and product berths, offshore loading facilities, bunker-barge berths and the Fujairah Anchorage Area. The port’s oil terminals are directly connected to numerous independent storage operators.
Refining cluster: Fujairah contains smaller refining, processing, blending and fuel-treatment facilities, but it is primarily a storage and trading hub rather than a major integrated refining centre comparable with Ruwais or Yanbu.
Crude flows: ADNOC’s approximately 406-kilometre Abu Dhabi Crude Oil Pipeline carries onshore Abu Dhabi crude to Fujairah. The pipeline has a design capacity of around 1.5 million barrels per day and gives ADNOC direct access to the Gulf of Oman without requiring tankers to pass through the Strait of Hormuz.
Connectivity: Connected by pipeline to Abu Dhabi’s onshore oil fields, by road to the wider UAE logistics network, and by sea to the Indian Ocean, South Asia, East Africa and global tanker routes
Main markets: United Arab Emirates, Gulf countries, India, Pakistan, East Africa, Singapore and the wider international fuel-oil and marine-fuel market
Bunkering role: One of the world’s three largest marine-fuel hubs. Fuels are stored in the Fujairah Oil Industry Zone, transferred through the port and delivered to vessels by dedicated bunker barges at the offshore anchorage.
Energy-transition role: Its large independent tankage, blending infrastructure and bunker-delivery network give Fujairah a natural platform for biofuel blends and future alternative marine fuels, although conventional petroleum products remain dominant. This is a forward-looking inference based on the port’s existing infrastructure.
Strategic role: The Middle East’s principal independent oil-storage and bunkering centre and a critical alternative export point outside the Strait of Hormuz
Risks: Regional military escalation, tanker incidents in the Gulf of Oman, fires or explosions in tank farms, pipeline interruptions, berth congestion, marine pollution and competition from other storage and bunkering centres</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>56.36724116055368</longitude>
				<latitude>25.19688629922907</latitude>
				<altitude>-2.974494977984209</altitude>
