		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="02F63AE6E93FCA0C0978">
			<name>Port of Moerdijk – Industrial &amp; Logistics Zone</name>
			<description>Hub: Port of Moerdijk – Industrial, Chemical &amp; Multimodal Logistics Hub
Classification: Major industrial, chemical, short-sea and inland logistics hub
Location: Moerdijk, North Brabant, Netherlands, between Rotterdam and Antwerp
Owner/Operator: Port of Moerdijk Authority
Main commodities: Chemicals, petroleum products, biofuels, containers, metals, industrial materials, project cargo, dry bulk and recyclable feedstocks
Industrial area: Approximately 2,635 hectares, hosting more than 400 companies active in chemicals, energy, recycling, manufacturing, storage and logistics.
Main facilities: Chemical plants, liquid-bulk terminals, container terminals, warehouses, distribution centres, recycling facilities and short-sea shipping infrastructure
Connectivity: Direct access by seagoing vessel, inland barge, rail, road and pipeline; strategically positioned on the Rotterdam–Antwerp industrial corridor
Container role: Important short-sea and inland-container hub, functioning partly as an extended gateway for Rotterdam’s Maasvlakte terminals
Main markets: Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, France and the wider European hinterland
Industrial integration: Strong focus on chemicals, energy, recycling and circular industrial processes
Energy-transition role: Circular chemistry, waste-to-feedstock projects, hydrogen infrastructure, renewable energy and lower-carbon logistics
Strategic role: Relieves congestion at larger ARA ports while connecting their industrial and logistics systems through multimodal infrastructure
Risks: Chemical accidents, fires, hazardous-material incidents, pipeline disruption, Rhine–Meuse waterway constraints, motorway congestion and environmental-permitting delays</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>4.608361461283297</longitude>
