		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Port of Rotterdam – Energy, Refining &amp; Logistics Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: Port of Rotterdam – Energy, Refining &amp; Maritime Logistics Hub
Classification: Global energy-trading, refining, storage and logistics hub
Location: Rotterdam–Rijnmond region, Netherlands, extending from the city of Rotterdam to Maasvlakte on the North Sea
Owner/Operator: Port of Rotterdam Authority; individual terminals, refineries and industrial facilities are operated by private companies
Main commodities: Crude oil, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, fuel oil, naphtha, LPG, LNG, biofuels, chemicals, edible oils, containers, coal and dry bulk
Main facilities: Crude and product terminals, independent tank farms, LNG import infrastructure, oil refineries, petrochemical plants, marine-bunkering facilities and extensive container terminals
Refining cluster: Includes the Shell Pernis, BP Rotterdam, ExxonMobil Rotterdam, Gunvor and Zeeland refining systems, alongside numerous chemical and fuel-processing plants
Crude flows: Historically around 95–100 million tonnes of crude oil per year enter Rotterdam, primarily supplying refineries in the Netherlands, Belgium and Germany.
Connectivity: Connected to the Rhine–Meuse inland-waterway system, European rail and road networks, and pipelines toward Antwerp, Amsterdam, Germany and inland Dutch industrial centres
Main markets: Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, France, Switzerland and the wider Northwest European trading market
Bunkering role: One of the world’s principal marine-fuel supply centres, handling conventional bunker fuels, LNG, biofuels and emerging low-carbon marine fuels
Energy-transition role: Development of hydrogen pipelines, carbon-transport and storage infrastructure, renewable-fuel plants, SAF, bio-refining and import chains for hydrogen derivatives. Rotterdam describes itself as Europe’s largest energy port, with more than 13% of European energy use flowing through the port.
Strategic role: Central physical hub of the ARA oil-products market and Northwest Europe’s main entry, processing, blending, storage and redistribution point for energy commodities
Risks: Refinery outages, power failures, labour disruption, Rhine water-level constraints, North Sea weather, port congestion, pipeline interruptions, fires, spills and stricter European carbon regulation</description>
