			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Port of Antwerp-Bruges – Refining &amp; Petrochemical Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: Port of Antwerp-Bruges – Refining, Chemical &amp; Maritime Logistics Hub
Classification: Major integrated refining, petrochemical, liquid-bulk and logistics hub
Location: Antwerp and Zeebrugge, Belgium
Owner/Operator: Port of Antwerp-Bruges Authority; industrial facilities and terminals are operated by private companies
Main commodities: Crude oil, refined petroleum products, chemicals, LPG, LNG, biofuels, fertilizers, containers, vehicles and breakbulk cargo
Main facilities: Oil refineries, steam crackers, chemical plants, independent tank terminals, pipeline networks, container terminals and LNG infrastructure at Zeebrugge
Refining cluster: Centred on the TotalEnergies Antwerp and ExxonMobil Antwerp refineries, with extensive integration into nearby petrochemical and storage facilities
Chemical integration: Antwerp hosts Europe’s largest integrated chemical cluster, where refineries, crackers, chemical producers and logistics operators exchange feedstocks, hydrogen, steam and intermediate products through pipeline networks.
Storage infrastructure: Large independent tank-storage sector handling crude, products, chemicals, gases and renewable feedstocks
Connectivity: Connected by pipeline, inland barge, rail and road to Rotterdam, the Rhine–Ruhr industrial region, France and Central Europe
Main markets: Belgium, Netherlands, Germany, France and wider European and international markets
Zeebrugge role: Major LNG import, storage and transshipment point, complementing Antwerp’s refining and chemical activity
Energy-transition role: Renewable methanol, hydrogen, carbon capture, chemical recycling, sustainable fuels and circular-plastics projects
Strategic role: One of the most integrated refining and chemical locations in the world, combining large-scale production with global maritime access and deep European hinterland connections
Risks: Chemical accidents, refinery and cracker outages, labour strikes, Scheldt navigation restrictions, pipeline disruption, port congestion, high European energy costs and tightening environmental regulation</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>4.405954877559444</longitude>
				<latitude>51.24654459390979</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0.4582657094533639</heading>
