		<Placemark>
			<name>Port of Amsterdam – Petroleum Products &amp; Storage Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: Port of Amsterdam – Petroleum Products, Storage &amp; Blending Hub
Classification: Major petroleum-products trading, storage and maritime logistics hub
Location: North Sea Canal area, Amsterdam, Netherlands
Owner/Operator: Port of Amsterdam Authority; storage terminals and industrial installations are privately operated
Main commodities: Gasoline, diesel, gasoil, fuel oil, naphtha, biofuels, base oils, chemicals, coal, agricultural products and containers
Primary energy role: Storage, blending, transshipment and trading of refined petroleum products rather than large-scale crude-oil refining
Main facilities: Independent product terminals, blending installations, barge-loading facilities, bunker-supply infrastructure and distribution warehouses
Connectivity: Access to the North Sea through IJmuiden, with inland-waterway links toward Rotterdam, Antwerp, the Rhine and European product markets
Main markets: Northwest Europe, West Africa, the Americas and international gasoline and middle-distillate markets
Trading role: Important component of the ARA benchmark market, particularly for gasoline blending, diesel, fuel oil and biofuel storage
Marine role: Supplies seagoing vessels and inland barges, while also supporting redistribution toward inland European markets
Energy-transition role: Development of renewable fuels, green methanol, hydrogen infrastructure, circular industries and cleaner marine-fuel bunkering. The port plans to phase out coal handling by 2030.
Strategic role: Complements Rotterdam by providing substantial flexible storage and blending capacity for refined products within the ARA trading system
Risks: Product contamination, tank fires, North Sea Canal access restrictions, labour disruption, environmental permitting, declining fossil-fuel demand and volatility in gasoline and bunker-fuel trade</description>
