		<Placemark>
			<name>Singapore–Jurong Island</name>
			<description>Hub: Singapore Port &amp; Jurong Island Energy and Chemicals Hub
Classification: Global oil-trading, refining, petrochemical, storage and bunkering hub
Location: Singapore Strait, centred on Jurong Island, Pulau Bukom and the western Singapore port zone
Owner/Coordination: Singapore government agencies including the Maritime and Port Authority of Singapore, JTC and the Economic Development Board; facilities are operated by international energy, chemical and terminal companies
Main commodities: Crude oil, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, fuel oil, naphtha, LPG, LNG, chemicals, biofuels, base oils and marine fuels
Main facilities: Large refineries, petrochemical complexes, independent tank terminals, LNG infrastructure, underground storage caverns, blending facilities and ship-to-ship bunkering operations
Refining cluster: Includes the ExxonMobil integrated complex and the Singapore Refining Company facility, alongside Aster’s Bukom refining and chemical platform
Storage and trading: Major regional base for Vitol, Trafigura, Glencore, Shell, BP, PetroChina and other commodity traders, linking Middle Eastern supply with Asian demand
Bunkering role: The world’s leading marine-fuel bunkering centre, handling conventional fuel oil, marine gasoil, LNG, biofuel blends, methanol trials and developing ammonia supply chains
Connectivity: Located at the entrance to the Strait of Malacca, directly on the principal maritime route linking the Middle East, Europe and Northeast Asia
Main markets: Southeast Asia, China, Japan, South Korea, Australia and wider Asia-Pacific markets
Industrial integration: Refineries and crackers supply feedstocks to chemical, polymer, lubricant and specialty-product plants across Jurong Island
Energy-transition role: Singapore is allocating additional Jurong Island land for renewable power, SAF, low-carbon ammonia, hydrogen-ready generation and energy storage.
Strategic role: Asia’s principal physical oil-trading and price-discovery centre, as well as one of the world’s most important bunkering, storage and refinery locations
Risks: Strait of Malacca congestion, dependence on imported feedstocks, refinery and terminal outages, petrochemical overcapacity, regional competition, fire and spill risks, and disruption of Middle Eastern supply routes</description>
			<LookAt>
