		<Placemark>
			<name>Ningbo–Zhoushan Port – Crude Import, Refining &amp; Bunkering Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: Ningbo–Zhoushan Port – Energy, Refining &amp; Maritime Logistics Hub
Classification: Major crude-import, refining, storage, bunkering and industrial port hub
Location: Zhejiang Province, eastern China, south of Shanghai
Owner/Operator: Ningbo Zhoushan Port Group; industrial terminals, refineries and storage assets are operated by multiple state-owned and private companies
Main commodities: Crude oil, refined products, LNG, LPG, fuel oil, petrochemicals, chemicals, iron ore, coal, containers and dry bulk
Main facilities: Deepwater crude terminals, liquid-bulk terminals, refinery-supply berths, storage farms, petrochemical complexes, LNG infrastructure and large container terminals
Refining and industrial role: The hub supplies major refinery and petrochemical systems in Zhejiang, including the Sinopec Zhenhai complex and the growing Zhoushan greenfield refining and chemicals zone
Crude-import role: One of China’s most important seaborne crude-oil gateways, receiving large Middle Eastern, Russian, Atlantic Basin and West African cargoes
Bunkering role: Zhoushan has become one of the world’s leading marine-fuel supply centres, especially for low-sulfur fuel oil and bonded bunker sales
Connectivity: Strong coastal-shipping, inland-distribution and pipeline links to eastern China’s industrial and consumer markets
Main markets: Eastern China, especially the Yangtze River Delta, as well as international shipping and bunkering markets
Energy-transition role: Development of LNG bunkering, cleaner marine fuels, petrochemical upgrading, green-methanol initiatives and lower-carbon logistics
Strategic role: One of the world’s largest cargo ports by total tonnage and a major gateway for China’s crude imports, refinery feedstocks and marine-fuel distribution
Risks: Typhoons, port congestion, refinery outages, petrochemical overcapacity, environmental constraints, shipping disruptions in the East China Sea and dependence on imported crude supplies</description>
