		<Placemark>
			<name>Ulsan Industrial Port – Refining &amp; Petrochemical Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: Ulsan Industrial Port – Refining, Petrochemical &amp; Maritime Logistics Hub
Classification: Major refining, petrochemical, storage and export hub
Location: Ulsan, southeastern coast of South Korea
Owner/Operator: Ulsan Port Authority; refineries and industrial installations are operated by companies including SK Energy and S-OIL
Main commodities: Crude oil, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, naphtha, LPG, marine fuels, lubricants, petrochemical feedstocks, chemicals and containers
Main facilities: Deepwater oil berths, refinery jetties, chemical terminals, tank farms, petrochemical plants, shipyards and industrial-storage infrastructure
Refining cluster: Home to the SK Energy Ulsan Complex and the S-OIL Onsan complex nearby, making the region one of Asia’s most concentrated refining areas
Industrial integration: Strong integration between refining, base oils, aromatics, polymers, petrochemicals and marine logistics
Export role: Major export outlet for refined products and petrochemicals to Northeast and Southeast Asia
Connectivity: Marine access to major Asian shipping routes, with strong road, industrial and pipeline links across South Korea
Main markets: South Korea, Japan, China, Southeast Asia and wider Asia-Pacific markets
Energy-transition role: Increasing focus on hydrogen, lower-carbon petrochemicals, bio-based fuels, CCUS initiatives and cleaner marine-fuel supply
Strategic role: One of Asia’s most important refining and petrochemical centres, supporting both domestic energy security and regional export markets
Risks: Dependence on imported crude, Strait of Hormuz exposure, typhoons, refinery outages, petrochemical margin weakness, fire risk and industrial accidents</description>
