		<Placemark>
			<name>Novorossiysk Port – Black Sea Oil Export &amp; Logistics Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: Novorossiysk Port – Oil Export, Storage &amp; Black Sea Logistics Hub
Classification: Major crude-oil, petroleum-products and maritime export hub
Location: Novorossiysk, Krasnodar Krai, Russian Black Sea coast
Owner/Operator: Port infrastructure involves multiple operators, including Transneft system assets and related terminal operators; the broader port includes commercial and industrial facilities
Main commodities: Crude oil, diesel, fuel oil, naphtha, petroleum products, grain, metals, containers and dry bulk
Main facilities: Oil-export terminals, storage depots, product-loading berths, commercial port facilities and access to offshore and coastal energy infrastructure
Oil-export role: One of Russia’s principal Black Sea export gateways for crude oil and petroleum products
Key energy assets: Includes the Sheskharis Oil Terminal and nearby offshore loading systems associated with the CPC export route for Kazakh crude
Connectivity: Linked to Russia’s domestic pipeline network and to inland storage systems; also connected to the Black Sea shipping lane through the Turkish Straits
Main markets: Mediterranean Europe, Turkey, Asia and other global destinations accessible via the Bosporus and Dardanelles
Strategic role: Critical outlet for Russian and regional seaborne oil exports from the Black Sea basin
Recent context: The hub has become increasingly sensitive to geopolitical and military disruption, with repeated attacks and temporary loading interruptions affecting export reliability
Energy-transition role: Limited compared with Western or Asian hubs; its main importance remains hydrocarbon export logistics
Risks: Drone and missile attacks, Black Sea security risks, Turkish Straits congestion, sanctions, terminal damage, port closures, adverse weather and pipeline-supply interruptions</description>
