		<Placemark>
			<name>Jebel Ali Port – Container, Industrial &amp; Maritime Logistics Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: Jebel Ali Port – Container, Industrial &amp; Maritime Logistics Hub
Classification: Global container, transshipment, industrial, free-zone and multimodal logistics hub
Location: Dubai, United Arab Emirates, on the southeastern coast of the Arabian Gulf
Owner/Operator: Operated by DP World UAE; the adjacent Jebel Ali Free Zone hosts thousands of manufacturing, trading, warehousing and logistics companies.
Main commodities: Containers, vehicles, steel, machinery, food products, chemicals, petrochemicals, petroleum products, project cargo, dry bulk, breakbulk and refrigerated cargo
Main facilities: Four container terminals, more than 100 berths, approximately 25 kilometres of quay, Ro-Ro and heavy-lift facilities, warehouses, distribution centres and direct integration with the Jebel Ali Free Zone. Annual container-handling capacity is approximately 19.4 million TEU.
Refining cluster: Includes ENOC’s Jebel Ali refinery, whose capacity was expanded from approximately 140,000 to 210,000 barrels per day, alongside lubricant plants, blending facilities, petrochemical storage and downstream industrial companies.
Crude flows: Jebel Ali is not a major regional crude-export terminal. Its oil activity is centred more on refinery feedstocks, refined products, petrochemicals, lubricants and industrial distribution than on large-scale crude exports.
Connectivity: Integrated with Jebel Ali Free Zone, Dubai’s motorway network, Al Maktoum International Airport, regional warehouses and short-sea connections throughout the Gulf
Main markets: United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia, Oman, the wider GCC, India, East Africa, Europe and Asia through international liner and transshipment services
Bunkering role: Provides marine fuels and ship services for vessels calling at Dubai, although Fujairah is the UAE’s dominant independent bunkering and fuel-oil trading centre
Energy-transition role: DP World has introduced terminal electrification, renewable electricity and large-scale rooftop solar installations across its UAE operations. Jebel Ali and associated DP World facilities have been supplied with renewable electricity, while port equipment is progressively being electrified.
Strategic role: The Middle East’s largest container and industrial logistics hub, functioning as the main distribution gateway between global shipping routes, Dubai and the wider Gulf economy.
Risks: Strait of Hormuz disruption, container congestion, cyberattacks, extreme heat, regional military tensions, power or equipment failures and competition from Khalifa Port, Hamad Port and Saudi logistics hubs</description>
