		<Placemark>
			<name>Ras Tanura–Juaymah</name>
			<description>Hub: Ras Tanura–Juaymah – Saudi Crude Oil Export &amp; Refining Hub
Classification: Global crude-oil export, LPG, refined-product and refining complex
Location: Eastern Province of Saudi Arabia, on the Arabian Gulf north of Dammam
Owner/Operator: Saudi Aramco owns and operates the principal port, loading, storage, pipeline and refining facilities.
Main commodities: Arabian Light, Arabian Extra Light, Arabian Medium and other Saudi crude grades, LPG, naphtha, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, fuel oil and sulphur
Main facilities: Ras Tanura North Pier, Sea Island crude-loading terminals, the Juaymah crude single-point mooring terminal, Juaymah LPG terminal, crude and product storage, pipeline connections and the Ras Tanura refinery. The offshore loading system is designed to accommodate deep-draft crude tankers.
Refining cluster: Centred on the approximately 550,000-barrel-per-day Ras Tanura refinery, which produces gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, naphtha, fuel oil and other petroleum products.
Crude flows: Receives crude from Saudi Arabia’s Eastern Province fields through Aramco’s extensive trunk-pipeline and storage network. Cargoes are loaded at fixed offshore terminals and Juaymah single-point moorings for export by large tankers.
Connectivity: Connected to Saudi Arabia’s major producing fields, stabilisation plants, storage systems, refineries and domestic product-distribution network
Main markets: Primarily Asian refining markets, including China, India, Japan and South Korea, alongside customers in the Middle East, Europe and other international markets
Bunkering role: Supplies bunker fuel and operational services to tankers calling at Aramco terminals, but it is not an independent open-market bunker hub comparable with Fujairah
Energy-transition role: Ras Tanura remains predominantly a conventional hydrocarbon-export complex. Its transition role is linked to Aramco’s wider investments in refinery efficiency, lower-carbon fuels, carbon capture, hydrogen and emissions reduction rather than to a dedicated renewable-fuel port cluster.
Strategic role: Saudi Arabia’s principal Arabian Gulf crude-export gateway and one of the most important physical loading centres in the global oil market
Risks: Strait of Hormuz disruption, military or drone attacks, offshore loading-system failures, pipeline interruption, refinery outages, marine accidents and concentration of export infrastructure in the Eastern Province</description>
