		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Yanbu Industrial Port</name>
			<description>Hub: Yanbu Industrial Port – Red Sea Crude, Refining &amp; Petrochemical Export Hub
Classification: Major crude-oil, refined-product, petrochemical and industrial export complex
Location: Yanbu Industrial City, western Saudi Arabia, on the Red Sea
Owner/Operator: King Fahd Industrial Port falls under the Saudi Ports Authority, while Saudi Aramco operates the principal crude and product terminals. Refineries and petrochemical plants are operated by Aramco and joint-venture companies.
Main commodities: Arabian Light and Arabian Super Light crude, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, fuel oil, LPG, naphtha, base oils, sulphur, petrochemicals and industrial bulk cargo
Main facilities: Yanbu North Crude Terminal, Yanbu South Terminal, refined-product terminals, tank farms, deep-water VLCC berths, petrochemical jetties and industrial cargo facilities. Some crude berths can accommodate vessels of up to approximately 500,000 DWT.
Refining cluster: Includes the approximately 400,000-barrel-per-day YASREF refinery, the more than 400,000-barrel-per-day SAMREF refinery and the separate Aramco Yanbu refinery, together with lubricant, petrochemical and downstream industrial facilities.
Crude flows: Crude is transported from eastern Saudi Arabia to Yanbu through the East–West Pipeline system. The Yanbu South Terminal added around 3 million barrels per day of West Coast export capability for Arabian Light and Arabian Super Light crude.
Connectivity: Connected by pipeline across Saudi Arabia to Eastern Province oil fields and by road and industrial infrastructure to the wider Yanbu refining and petrochemical complex
Main markets: Mediterranean Europe, Northwest Europe, Africa, the Americas and Asia through the Red Sea, Suez Canal and Bab el-Mandeb routes
Bunkering role: Provides marine fuels and services for tankers and industrial vessels calling at Yanbu, but it is primarily an export and refinery port rather than an international bunker-trading hub
Energy-transition role: Current initiatives focus mainly on refinery efficiency, digitalisation, water recycling and future petrochemical integration. Yanbu refinery has implemented major digital improvements, while industrial operators are developing circular-water and resource-efficiency projects.
Strategic role: Saudi Arabia’s principal Red Sea oil-export outlet, allowing crude and products to reach European and Atlantic markets without passing through the Strait of Hormuz
Risks: Disruption to the East–West Pipeline, Bab el-Mandeb and Red Sea security risks, Suez Canal disruption, refinery outages, industrial accidents and concentration of large processing facilities in one coastal cluster</description>
