		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Ras Laffan Port</name>
			<description>Hub: Ras Laffan Port – Global LNG, Condensate Refining &amp; Gas-Processing Hub
Classification: Global LNG-export, gas-processing, condensate-refining and petrochemical hub
Location: Ras Laffan Industrial City, northeastern Qatar, approximately 80 kilometres north of Doha
Owner/Operator: QatarEnergy owns, regulates and operates Ras Laffan Port, while QatarEnergy LNG and its partners operate the LNG, condensate, GTL and associated processing facilities.
Main commodities: LNG, condensate, LPG, naphtha, jet fuel, diesel, GTL gasoil, GTL base oils, helium, ethane, sulphur and petrochemical products.
Main facilities: LNG liquefaction trains, LNG storage tanks and loading berths, Q-Flex and Q-Max carrier facilities, non-LNG product terminals, two condensate refineries, Pearl GTL, Oryx GTL, helium plants, sulphur-handling facilities and extensive offshore-to-onshore gas pipelines. QatarEnergy describes Ras Laffan as the world’s largest LNG-export facility.
Refining cluster: Includes Laffan Refinery 1 and 2, with a combined condensate-processing capacity of approximately 306,600 barrels per stream day, as well as the Pearl and Oryx gas-to-liquids facilities.
Crude flows: Ras Laffan is not primarily a crude-oil export port. Its hydrocarbon flows originate mainly as natural gas and associated condensate from Qatar’s offshore North Field, transported to shore through subsea pipelines for liquefaction, refining and processing.
Connectivity: Directly connected by offshore pipelines to the North Field, by domestic pipelines to Qatar’s gas and industrial network, and by specialised LNG carriers to global importing terminals
Main markets: China, India, Japan, South Korea, Europe and other global LNG-importing regions, together with international markets for condensate, LPG, GTL products and sulphur
Bunkering role: Provides specialised fuel, loading and marine services for LNG and product carriers, but it is not a major independent spot-bunkering and fuel-trading hub
Energy-transition role: QatarEnergy is integrating energy-efficiency technologies and carbon-capture systems into its LNG expansion projects, while modernising its LNG fleet with more efficient dual-fuel vessels. The strategy is centred on lowering the carbon intensity of LNG rather than replacing gas exports.
Strategic role: The central export gateway for Qatar’s North Field and one of the most important LNG-production and loading complexes in the global gas market
Risks: Strait of Hormuz disruption, LNG-train outages, military attacks, offshore-pipeline failures, highly concentrated production infrastructure, technical problems affecting specialised LNG equipment and dependence on safe access for LNG carriers</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>51.5255214</longitude>
				<latitude>25.91176160000001</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
