				<coordinates>51.57061380662287,25.92631529916464,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Tanger Med Port</name>
			<description>Hub: Tanger Med – Container, Industrial &amp; Hydrocarbon Logistics Hub
Classification: Global container-transshipment, industrial, Ro-Ro, hydrocarbon-storage and maritime-logistics hub
Location: Northern Morocco, on the Strait of Gibraltar, approximately 40 kilometres east of Tangier
Owner/Operator: Tanger Med Port Authority manages the port complex, while specialised terminals operate under concessions involving international and Moroccan operators, including APM Terminals, Eurogate and Marsa Maroc.
Main commodities: Containers, vehicles, refined petroleum products, marine fuels, industrial goods, agricultural products, general cargo and dry bulk
Main facilities: Four container terminals, Ro-Ro and passenger terminals, two vehicle terminals, a hydrocarbon terminal, general-cargo facilities, rail infrastructure and extensive logistics and industrial zones. The container terminals handled more than 11.1 million TEU in 2025.
Refining cluster: No major refinery is directly located within the port. Tanger Med primarily handles the import, export, storage, blending and redistribution of refined petroleum products.
Crude flows: Tanger Med is not a major crude-oil loading centre. Its liquid-bulk activity is dominated by refined products and marine fuels; the port handled approximately 8.64 million tonnes of liquid bulk in 2025.
Connectivity: Directly connected to more than 180 ports in over 70 countries, with road and rail links to Morocco’s principal industrial centres and automotive plants.
Main markets: Morocco, Spain, France, West Africa, Mediterranean Europe, Northern Europe, the Americas and Asia
Bunkering role: Important bunkering centre at the western entrance to the Mediterranean. Its hydrocarbon terminal has approximately 532,000 m³ of refined-product storage and an annual handling capacity of about 15 million tonnes.
Energy-transition role: Since January 2025, the Tanger Med port complex has been supplied with 100% green electricity. Further decarbonisation measures include port-equipment electrification, energy-efficiency improvements and preparations for shore-power services.
Strategic role: Africa’s leading container-transshipment hub and a major maritime bridge between Europe, Africa and Atlantic–Mediterranean shipping routes
Risks: Strait of Gibraltar congestion, strong winds, container-network disruption, cyberattacks, labour disruption, equipment failures, hydrocarbon spills and dependence on international transshipment activity</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-5.507808571271255</longitude>
				<latitude>35.87192904163241</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
