				<gx:drawOrder>1</gx:drawOrder>
				<coordinates>-5.515828994314563,35.88927781581516,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Lagos–Lekki Maritime and Energy Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: Lagos–Lekki – Deep-Sea Port, Refining &amp; Petroleum-Products Hub
Classification: Deep-sea container, petroleum-refining, petrochemical, liquid-bulk and industrial-logistics hub
Location: Ibeju-Lekki, Lagos State, Nigeria, on the Gulf of Guinea east of the traditional Apapa and Tin Can Island port complexes
Owner/Operator: Lekki Port LFTZ Enterprise Limited develops and manages Lekki Deep Sea Port under Nigerian port supervision, while the Nigerian Ports Authority provides regulatory and marine services. Dangote Industries separately owns and operates the adjacent refinery and its dedicated marine facilities.
Main commodities: Containers, crude oil, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, naphtha, LPG, polypropylene, fertilisers, petrochemicals, dry bulk and general cargo
Main facilities: A deep-water container terminal with a 1,200-metre quay, three container berths and a design capacity of approximately 2.7 million TEU annually; a dry-bulk berth; a liquid-bulk berth connected to nearby tank farms; and the separate Dangote refinery marine-loading system.
Refining cluster: Centred on the Dangote Petroleum Refinery, designed to process approximately 650,000 barrels of crude oil per day. The complex also incorporates petrochemical, polypropylene, storage, power-generation and fertiliser infrastructure.
Crude flows: Nigerian and international crude grades are delivered to the Dangote complex through dedicated offshore marine infrastructure. Refined products are distributed into the Nigerian market and exported by tanker to regional and international buyers.
Connectivity: Integrated with the Lagos Free Zone and connected by road and potential barge services to Lagos, Nigeria’s domestic distribution system and the wider West African market.
Main markets: Nigeria, Benin, Togo, Ghana, other West and Central African markets, Europe, the Americas and international Atlantic Basin product markets
Bunkering role: The hub has the physical potential to supply marine fuels through its large refinery and liquid-bulk infrastructure, although it is not yet an established international bunkering centre comparable with Fujairah or Tanger Med.
Energy-transition role: Its principal near-term contribution is producing modern, lower-sulphur transport fuels closer to African demand centres and reducing long-distance refined-product imports. It remains fundamentally a conventional petroleum-refining hub rather than a renewable-fuels cluster. This is an assessment based on the refinery’s current configuration.
Strategic role: Nigeria’s most important emerging downstream-energy hub, combining Africa’s largest refinery complex with a modern deep-sea port capable of supporting domestic supply and regional product exports
Risks: Refinery outages, crude-feedstock constraints, port-access congestion, foreign-exchange and regulatory uncertainty, pipeline or storage incidents, Gulf of Guinea maritime security risks and concentration around a single very large processing complex</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>3.773063504702934</longitude>
