		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Port of Durban</name>
			<description>Hub: Port of Durban – Container, Fuel Import &amp; Southern African Logistics Hub
Classification: Major container, automotive, liquid-bulk, general-cargo, bunkering and regional distribution hub
Location: Durban, KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa, on the western Indian Ocean
Owner/Operator: Transnet National Ports Authority manages the port in a landlord capacity. Transnet Port Terminals operates the principal container, automotive and bulk terminals, while private companies operate liquid-bulk and petroleum-storage facilities.
Main commodities: Containers, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, fuel oil, chemicals, LPG, vehicles, agricultural products, steel, breakbulk and general cargo
Main facilities: Durban Container Terminal, Pier 1 and Pier 2, the Island View liquid-bulk precinct, automotive terminals, Maydon Wharf bulk facilities, ship-repair infrastructure and petroleum-product storage and distribution terminals.
Refining cluster: Durban historically contained South Africa’s largest refining cluster, including the approximately 180,000-barrel-per-day SAPREF refinery. SAPREF has been inactive since 2022, and the port’s current energy role is increasingly focused on fuel imports, storage and distribution rather than operating crude refining.
Crude flows: Crude imports historically supplied Durban’s refineries. With the contraction of South African refining capacity, flows have increasingly shifted toward imported gasoline, diesel, jet fuel and other finished products. The Island View precinct reportedly handles around 70% of South Africa’s fuel imports.
Connectivity: Connected by road and rail to Johannesburg, Gauteng and the wider Southern African hinterland. Petroleum products move inland through storage terminals, road and rail gantries and the New Multi-Product Pipeline.
Main markets: South Africa, Botswana, Zimbabwe, Zambia, Eswatini, Lesotho and other Southern African markets
Bunkering role: One of Southern Africa’s principal bunkering ports, supplying fuel oil and marine gasoil to container ships, bulk carriers and tankers on Indian Ocean and Cape routes. Bunkering is generally performed alongside designated berths.
Energy-transition role: A proposed LNG-import, gas-fired power and LNG-bunkering development is being advanced for the Durban port area, but it remains a planned project rather than an operating facility.
Strategic role: South Africa’s principal container gateway and its most important coastal entry and distribution point for imported transport fuels serving the country’s largest inland demand centres
Risks: Container congestion, road and rail bottlenecks, flooding, power failures, labour disruption, fuel-import dependence, limited bunker availability, terminal fires, pipeline interruptions and prolonged outages at former refining facilities</description>
