		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Port of Saldanha Bay</name>
			<description>Hub: Saldanha Bay – Crude Storage, Iron-Ore Export &amp; Energy Logistics Hub
Classification: Deep-water crude-storage, strategic petroleum-reserve, LPG, iron-ore and industrial export hub
Location: Western Cape, South Africa, approximately 110 kilometres north of Cape Town
Owner/Operator: Transnet National Ports Authority manages the port. Transnet Port Terminals operates the iron-ore facilities, the Strategic Fuel Fund operates the principal crude-storage complex, and Sunrise Energy operates the LPG-import terminal.
Main commodities: Crude oil, LPG, propane, butane, iron ore, manganese, refined petroleum products and industrial bulk cargo
Main facilities: Deep-water iron-ore loading berths and stockyards, a crude-oil jetty capable of receiving very large tankers, pipelines to strategic storage, the Sunrise LPG terminal and the adjacent Freeport Saldanha industrial-development zone
Refining cluster: No major refinery is directly located within the port. Saldanha functions primarily as a crude-storage, strategic-reserve, LPG-import and bulk-export centre.
Crude flows: Crude can be imported, stored, blended and subsequently re-exported. The Strategic Fuel Fund facility contains six large underground concrete tanks with total capacity of approximately 45 million barrels.
Connectivity: Connected by the dedicated iron-ore railway to mining regions in South Africa’s Northern Cape, by pipelines to crude and LPG storage facilities and by road to the Western Cape industrial market
Main markets: China and other Asian iron-ore markets, European and Asian crude traders, and South African domestic LPG and fuel markets
Bunkering role: Limited compared with Durban or Tanger Med. Saldanha can supply fuels and marine services to visiting bulk carriers and tankers, but its principal role is storage and bulk-cargo handling rather than open-market bunkering.
Energy-transition role: Saldanha Bay has been designated as a priority location for future green-hydrogen production, hydrogen derivatives, low-carbon industrial development and potential export infrastructure. Most large projects remain in the planning or development phase.
Strategic role: South Africa’s principal strategic crude-storage location and its dominant deep-water iron-ore export gateway, positioned close to shipping routes around the Cape of Good Hope
Risks: Atlantic weather, iron-ore railway disruption, storage-system failures, crude-market volatility, project delays, marine pollution, limited local refining demand and dependence on a small number of large specialised terminals</description>
