		<Placemark>
			<name>Djibouti–Doraleh Port Complex</name>
			<description>Hub: Djibouti–Doraleh – Red Sea Transit, Fuel Import &amp; Horn of Africa Logistics Hub
Classification: Strategic container, petroleum-import, multipurpose-cargo and regional transit hub
Location: Djibouti City and Doraleh, on the Gulf of Tadjoura near the southern entrance to the Red Sea and the Bab el-Mandeb Strait
Owner/Operator: The Djibouti Ports and Free Zones Authority oversees the national port system. Doraleh’s container, multipurpose and petroleum facilities are operated through specialised state-controlled and commercial entities, including the Horizon Djibouti oil terminal.
Main commodities: Containers, diesel, gasoline, jet fuel, fuel oil, LPG, edible oils, grain, fertilisers, vehicles, construction materials and general cargo
Main facilities: Doraleh container facilities, the Doraleh Multipurpose Port, the Horizon petroleum terminal, free zones, rail-connected logistics platforms and the newer Damerjog liquid-bulk development. The existing Horizon terminal provides approximately 371,000 m³ of storage capacity.
Refining cluster: No major operating refinery is currently integrated into the established Doraleh port complex. Longer-term Damerjog industrial plans have included a refinery and additional tank-storage infrastructure, but these should be treated as development projects rather than established refining capacity.
Crude flows: Djibouti’s petroleum activity is dominated by imports of finished products for domestic use and onward delivery to Ethiopia. It is not currently a major crude-oil production or export centre.
Connectivity: Connected to Addis Ababa through the Addis–Djibouti railway and the principal road corridor. More than 95% of Ethiopia’s import-export trade by volume uses the Djibouti corridor.
Main markets: Djibouti, Ethiopia and, potentially, other landlocked markets in the Horn of Africa and East Africa
Bunkering role: Strategically positioned to supply ships operating between the Indian Ocean, Red Sea and Suez Canal, although its bunker market remains smaller than major global hubs such as Fujairah
Energy-transition role: Current development remains centred primarily on petroleum logistics and trade-corridor expansion. Port authorities have introduced some solar and efficiency initiatives, while larger low-carbon fuel activity remains limited.
Strategic role: Principal maritime gateway for landlocked Ethiopia and a strategically located logistics and fuel-supply centre immediately adjacent to the Bab el-Mandeb shipping chokepoint
Risks: Red Sea military activity, attacks on commercial shipping, disruption at Bab el-Mandeb, dependence on Ethiopian transit trade, road and railway congestion, regional instability, port competition and petroleum-storage or marine-pollution incidents</description>
