		<Placemark>
			<name>Port of Corpus Christi</name>
			<description>Hub: Port of Corpus Christi – U.S. Crude Oil Export &amp; Trading Hub
Classification: Global crude-oil export, storage, pipeline and refinery-supply hub
Location: Corpus Christi Bay and the Ingleside area, southern Texas, on the Gulf Coast
Owner/Operator: Port of Corpus Christi Authority manages the ship channel and public infrastructure; crude terminals, tank farms, refineries and pipelines are operated by private midstream and refining companies
Main commodities: WTI Midland, Eagle Ford crude, condensate and smaller volumes of imported crude and refined petroleum products
Main facilities: Large crude-export terminals at Ingleside and Corpus Christi, refinery docks, independent tank farms, pipeline manifolds, barge facilities and deep-water tanker berths
Refining cluster: Several refineries operate around Corpus Christi, but the port’s defining role has shifted from refinery supply toward large-scale exports of Permian Basin crude
Crude flows: Receives crude primarily from the Permian Basin and Eagle Ford through several long-distance pipelines. During 2025 and the first five months of 2026, crude exports generally exceeded 2 million barrels per day and represented approximately 93–97% of outbound crude movements.
Connectivity: Direct pipeline connections to the Permian Basin and Eagle Ford, with additional links to regional refineries, storage terminals and the wider Texas pipeline network
Main markets: Europe, particularly the Netherlands, United Kingdom, Spain, Italy and France; Asia, including South Korea and India; and selected Latin American markets
Bunkering role: Marine-fuel services are available, but bunkering is secondary to crude loading and export operations
Energy-transition role: Proposed carbon-management, hydrogen and low-carbon-fuel projects are emerging around Corpus Christi, although crude exports remain overwhelmingly dominant
Strategic role: The leading U.S. crude-oil export gateway and the principal maritime outlet for WTI Midland and other Permian grades. The port describes itself as the country’s largest energy-export gateway.
Risks: Hurricanes, fog, channel closures, pipeline outages, terminal concentration, oil spills, ship collisions and congestion during periods of exceptionally high export demand</description>
