		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Houston Ship Channel</name>
			<description>Hub: Houston Ship Channel – Crude Trading, Refining &amp; Storage Hub
Classification: Global crude-oil trading, refinery-supply, export, storage and pipeline hub
Location: Houston–Galveston region, Texas, extending from Houston through Galveston Bay to the Gulf Coast
Owner/Operator: Port Houston maintains and develops the ship channel and operates public terminals; private companies operate the crude terminals, refineries, storage tanks and pipelines
Main commodities: WTI Midland, Eagle Ford crude, imported medium and heavy sour crudes, condensate and refinery feedstocks
Main facilities: Private crude docks, refinery terminals, independent storage facilities, blending systems, barge terminals and major pipeline junctions throughout Houston, Pasadena, Deer Park, Baytown and Galena Park
Refining cluster: One of the largest refining clusters in the world, including major facilities around Baytown, Deer Park, Pasadena and the eastern Houston Ship Channel. Texas holds about one-third of total U.S. refining capacity, much of it concentrated along Gulf Coast ports.
Crude flows: Receives Permian and Eagle Ford crude through multiple pipelines, Cushing-origin crude through the Seaway system and imported sour crude by tanker. Crude can be processed locally, moved to neighbouring refineries or exported internationally
Connectivity: Connected to Cushing, the Permian Basin, Eagle Ford, Texas storage centres, Gulf Coast refineries, the Gulf Intracoastal Waterway and extensive barge and pipeline networks
Main markets: U.S. Gulf Coast refiners, Europe, Asia, Canada and Latin America
Bunkering role: Major Gulf Coast bunker-fuel and vessel-service centre, although its crude-trading role is more important for this category
Energy-transition role: Houston’s pipeline, storage, refinery and salt-cavern infrastructure is supporting carbon-capture, hydrogen, renewable-fuel and lower-carbon industrial projects
Strategic role: The most diversified U.S. crude-trading and refining hub. Unlike Corpus Christi, which is primarily export-oriented, Houston combines imports, exports, storage, blending, pipeline redistribution and very large refinery demand. Crude export tonnage through the region increased strongly during the first part of 2026.
Risks: Hurricanes, flooding, fog, ship-channel collisions, refinery accidents, pipeline interruptions, power failures, congestion and environmental restrictions</description>
