		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Port Arthur–Beaumont / Sabine–Neches Waterway</name>
			<description>Hub: Port Arthur–Beaumont – Crude Import, Refining &amp; Pipeline Hub
Classification: Major crude-import, refinery-supply, storage and petroleum-export corridor
Location: Sabine–Neches Waterway, southeastern Texas, close to the Louisiana border
Owner/Operator: Public marine infrastructure is managed by the ports of Port Arthur and Beaumont; private companies operate refinery docks, crude terminals, pipelines and tank farms
Main commodities: Domestic light crude, imported heavy and medium sour crude, refinery feedstocks and smaller crude-export volumes
Main facilities: Refinery marine terminals, private crude docks, storage tanks, pipeline connections and deep-water tanker facilities along the Sabine–Neches Waterway
Refining cluster: Includes the Motiva Port Arthur, ExxonMobil Beaumont, Valero Port Arthur and TotalEnergies Port Arthur refining systems. Motiva and ExxonMobil operate two of the largest refineries in the United States.
Crude flows: Receives domestic crude from Texas producing regions and imported grades suited to the corridor’s complex refineries. The crude is principally processed locally rather than re-exported
Connectivity: Connected to Texas and Louisiana crude pipelines, regional storage hubs, the Gulf Intracoastal Waterway, railway systems and inland product pipelines
Main markets: Port Arthur and Beaumont refineries, other Gulf Coast processors and international buyers of the resulting refined products
Bunkering role: Provides marine fuels and vessel services, but tanker unloading and refinery supply are its principal crude-related functions
Energy-transition role: Renewable diesel, SAF, carbon-management and lower-carbon industrial projects are developing within the corridor, alongside the existing conventional refining industry
Strategic role: One of the most important U.S. destinations for imported and domestic refinery feedstock. It is more accurately classified as a crude intake and refining hub than as a pure export hub
Risks: Hurricanes, flooding, refinery fires and explosions, hazardous-material releases, pipeline failures, channel congestion and dependence on a highly concentrated refining complex</description>
