			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>LOOP–Clovelly–St. James Crude Hub</name>
			<description>Hub: LOOP–Clovelly–St. James – Deep-Water Crude Trading, Storage &amp; Pipeline Hub
Classification: Deep-water crude import-and-export, storage, blending and inland-distribution hub
Location: LOOP Marine Terminal approximately 18 nautical miles offshore Louisiana, connected to the onshore Clovelly storage hub and St. James crude-trading centre
Owner/Operator: LOOP LLC operates the offshore terminal, subsea pipelines and Clovelly Hub; several private companies operate connected storage and pipeline infrastructure around St. James
Main commodities: Imported medium and heavy crude, Gulf of Mexico crude, domestic light crude and export cargoes
Main facilities: Offshore deep-water tanker terminal, subsea pipelines, Clovelly crude-storage facilities, metering and blending infrastructure, the LOCAP pipeline and connections to St. James and Capline
Refining cluster: No refinery is located at the offshore terminal itself. The system supplies major Louisiana refineries, including plants along the Lower Mississippi River, and connects to inland refining markets
Crude flows: LOOP can both unload and load deep-draft crude tankers. Crude moves between the offshore terminal, Clovelly storage and St. James, where it can enter Capline and pipelines supplying Louisiana and Midwest refineries.
Connectivity: Connected to the Clovelly Hub, St. James, Capline, LOCAP and pipelines serving Louisiana, the Midwest and other Gulf Coast markets
Main markets: Louisiana refineries, Midwest refiners, international crude suppliers and overseas buyers of U.S. crude
Bunkering role: Not an open-market bunker hub; operations are specialised around crude tankers and terminal support
Energy-transition role: Limited direct transition role because the complex is purpose-built for crude handling, although emissions management and operational-efficiency projects may reduce its footprint
Strategic role: The only currently operating U.S. offshore deep-water crude port capable of directly handling fully laden VLCC-scale cargoes. LOOP has handled more than 15 billion barrels of crude since beginning operations.
Risks: Hurricanes, offshore equipment failures, subsea-pipeline incidents, oil spills, storage interruptions and disruption to the LOCAP or Capline systems</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-90.22457012593216</longitude>
				<latitude>30.23964645435963</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-0.06644171407397513</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>125516.6760459274</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ferry</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<gx:drawOrder>1</gx:drawOrder>
				<coordinates>-90.14741524227848,30.19062721127204,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Port Freeport</name>
			<description>Hub: Port Freeport – Crude Export, Storage &amp; Pipeline Hub
Classification: Crude-oil export, NGL, petrochemical and refinery-supply port
Location: Freeport, Texas, approximately 60 miles south of Houston
Owner/Operator: Port Freeport manages the navigation channel and public facilities; private companies operate crude terminals, pipelines and storage infrastructure
Main commodities: Domestic crude oil, condensate, natural-gas liquids, chemicals and refinery feedstocks
Main facilities: Private crude docks, pipeline-connected tank farms, marine terminals and nearby petrochemical and refining infrastructure
Refining cluster: No very large refinery is located directly inside the public port, although the nearby Sweeny refining and petrochemical system creates regional feedstock demand
Crude flows: Handles crude delivered from inland Texas and pipeline systems for export or regional refinery supply. The Seaway system includes marine dock infrastructure at Freeport and links Gulf Coast terminals with Cushing and Houston-area markets.
Connectivity: Connected to the Seaway system, Texas crude pipelines, regional tank farms, Gulf Coast refineries and the Gulf Intracoastal Waterway
Main markets: U.S. Gulf Coast refiners, Europe and other international markets receiving U.S. light crude
Bunkering role: Secondary to crude, NGL and chemical cargo operations
Energy-transition role: Potential support location for carbon-management and lower-carbon industrial projects, but current crude and NGL movements remain central
Strategic role: A secondary but still important Texas crude-export and pipeline port. Port Freeport continues to identify itself as a leading U.S. exporter of crude oil and natural-gas liquids.
Risks: Hurricanes, channel closures, pipeline disruptions, oil spills, competition from Corpus Christi and Houston and dependence on private terminal availability</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-95.31551251396318</longitude>
				<latitude>28.93311774742469</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0.009555947072116471</heading>
