			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Valdez Marine Terminal</name>
			<description>Hub: Valdez Marine Terminal – Alaska North Slope Crude Loading Hub
Classification: Crude-oil pipeline terminus, storage and tanker-loading terminal
Location: Port Valdez, Prince William Sound, southern Alaska
Owner/Operator: Alyeska Pipeline Service Company
Main commodities: Alaska North Slope crude oil
Main facilities: Crude metering, storage tanks, two operational tanker-loading berths, vapour-management systems, ballast-water treatment and dedicated oil-spill-response infrastructure
Refining cluster: No major refinery is located at Valdez; the terminal loads crude onto tankers for delivery to external refineries
Crude flows: Receives Alaska North Slope crude through the 800-mile Trans-Alaska Pipeline System. The terminal currently has 13 tanks in service, working inventory capacity of approximately 6.6 million barrels and two operational loading berths.
Connectivity: Direct connection to North Slope production through TAPS and tanker routes through Prince William Sound to Pacific Coast refineries
Main markets: Primarily refineries in Washington State and California
Bunkering role: Provides operational services for crude tankers but is not an open-market marine-fuel centre
Energy-transition role: Limited; the terminal remains dedicated to conventional crude, although its vapour-recovery system generates part of the facility’s electricity
Strategic role: The sole maritime loading outlet for crude transported through TAPS. It is an essential crude-export and transportation terminal, although it is less of a flexible international trading hub than Corpus Christi, Houston or LOOP
Risks: Earthquakes, avalanches, extreme weather, tanker accidents, oil spills, pipeline failures and declining throughput from mature North Slope production</description>
