		<Placemark>
			<name>Port of Skikda</name>
			<description>Hub: Port of Skikda – Hydrocarbon, LNG &amp; Maritime Logistics Hub
Alternative name: Port El Djedid / New Port of Skikda
Classification: Major crude-oil, refined-products, LNG and petrochemical export hub
Location: Skikda, northeastern Mediterranean coast of Algeria
Owner/Operator: Entreprise Portuaire de Skikda; hydrocarbon assets and loading systems are closely integrated with Sonatrach operations
Main commodities: Crude oil, condensate, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, naphtha, fuel oil, LPG, LNG, aromatics, chemicals, grain and general cargo
Hydrocarbon transit capacity: Approximately 30 million tonnes per year
Main facilities: Dedicated oil and gas berths, LNG berths, product-loading jetties, tank farms, refinery connections, two offshore single-point mooring systems and conventional commercial-port facilities
Berths and vessel size: The new port includes specialized berths for crude oil, products, LPG, aromatics and LNG. Its crude berth can handle vessels of around 100,000 DWT, while two offshore SPMs can serve VLCC-scale tankers of approximately 320,000 tonnes or more
Loading rates: Offshore crude-loading buoys are rated at approximately 10,000 m³/hour; the main crude and fuel-oil berth can load at up to about 6,500 m³/hour
Connected infrastructure: Algerian inland crude and product pipeline network, RA1K refinery, RA2K condensate refinery, GL1K LNG plant, storage farms and petrochemical facilities
Main markets: Algeria, Mediterranean Europe and international crude, refined-product and LNG markets
Strategic role: One of Algeria’s three principal petroleum ports and the main maritime outlet for the Skikda refining, LNG and petrochemical industrial zone
Risks: Tanker accidents, oil spills, LNG incidents, industrial fires, berth outages, Mediterranean weather, port congestion and disruption to inland pipeline supplies</description>
