		<Placemark id="0B6901C6983F22D4E303">
			<name>Point Lisas Industrial Estate (Ammonia facilities)</name>
			<description>Facility: Point Lisas Industrial Estate – Ammonia Production Complex
Classification: Major natural-gas-based ammonia and fertilizer hub
Location: Point Lisas, Couva, west coast of Trinidad, Trinidad and Tobago
Estate/Port operator: Point Lisas Industrial Port Development Corporation — PLIPDECO
Main operators: Proman, Nutrien, Yara/Tringen and Point Lisas Nitrogen Limited
Main feedstock: Natural gas supplied from Trinidad and Tobago’s offshore gas fields through the national pipeline network
Main products: Anhydrous ammonia, urea, urea-ammonium-nitrate solution, melamine and related nitrogen fertilizers
Ammonia capacity: The Point Lisas ammonia industry comprises about 11 plants with total nominal capacity of approximately 5.2 million tonnes per year.
Key facilities: Nutrien’s nitrogen complex, Proman’s CNC and N2000 plants, Yara/Tringen facilities, the AUM complex and the Point Lisas Nitrogen plant
Proman capacity: The CNC and N2000 ammonia plants together have approximately 1.3 million tonnes per year of production capacity.
Point Lisas Nitrogen capacity: Approximately 650,000 tonnes per year; the plant is one of the estate’s large single-train ammonia facilities.
Port infrastructure: Ammonia and fertilizer products are exported through dedicated marine berths connected to the production and storage facilities. PLIPDECO coordinates vessel movements, while specialized berths are operated within the National Energy port system.
Main export markets: United States, Latin America, Europe, the Caribbean and other Atlantic markets
Industrial integration: Carbon dioxide generated during ammonia production is supplied to neighbouring methanol, urea and chemical plants, creating a highly integrated petrochemical cluster
Strategic role: One of the world’s most concentrated ammonia-production and export hubs and a central pillar of Trinidad and Tobago’s downstream natural-gas industry
Recent operational issues: Production has been affected by domestic natural-gas shortages, weak plant utilization and port-access disputes. Nutrien initiated a controlled shutdown of its Trinidad nitrogen operations in October 2025 following restrictions on port access.
Risks: Natural-gas supply curtailment, ageing plants, port-access disputes, ammonia leaks, fire and explosion hazards, hurricanes, international fertilizer-price volatility and carbon-emissions regulation</description>
