	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>Pipelines crude</name>
		<Placemark id="ADDMVL00000000000001">
			<name>Rostock–Schwedt Pipeline (MVL)</name>
			<description><![CDATA[Classification: Crude oil pipeline — Baltic import route (Mineralölverbundleitung, MVL)<br>Route: Rostock oil port (Baltic Sea) → PCK Schwedt refinery, ~200 km<br>Owner/Operator: PCK Raffinerie GmbH<br>Capacity: Limited — historically able to load the refinery at roughly half its nameplate; a ~€400 million upgrade has been pursued to raise throughput<br>Status: Operational — became Schwedt's lifeline after Germany ended Russian pipeline crude imports in January 2023<br>Strategic role: The substitute artery for the Druzhba supply that fed Schwedt for five decades; seaborne barrels landed at Rostock reach the Berlin fuel market through this line<br>Risks: Capacity bottleneck versus refinery nameplate; dependence on Baltic tanker deliveries and port logistics]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_icon?color=1976d2&amp;id=2000&amp;scale=47</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
				<tessellate>1</tessellate>
				<coordinates>
					12.12,54.13650000000001,0 12.52,53.90000000000001,0 13.05,53.65000000000001,0 13.6,53.42,0 14.02,53.21999999999999,0 14.2365,53.0745,0 
				</coordinates>
			</LineString>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="ADDFPS00000000000001">
			<name>Forties Pipeline System (FPS)</name>
			<description><![CDATA[Classification: Integrated crude oil and NGL transport system<br>Route: Forties Unity platform (central North Sea) → Cruden Bay landfall (169 km offshore) → Kinneil, Grangemouth (209 km onshore) → Dalmeny tank farm → Hound Point export jetty<br>Owner/Operator: INEOS (acquired from BP in 2017)<br>Capacity: Nominal ~575,000–610,000 b/d; carries liquids from ~85 UK and Norwegian fields — roughly 40% of UK North Sea oil<br>Main products: Stabilised Forties Blend crude delivered at Hound Point (a Dated Brent benchmark grade); gas liquids to Grangemouth<br>Strategic role: The upstream leg of the Forties chain on this map — wellhead to Hound Point loading to Rotterdam; a single-system chokepoint for a large share of UK production<br>Risks: Single-system concentration — outages at Kinneil or on the main line ripple directly into the Dated Brent benchmark; ageing infrastructure; declining North Sea throughput]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_icon?color=1976d2&amp;id=2000&amp;scale=47</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
				<tessellate>1</tessellate>
				<coordinates>
					0.9,57.73,0 -1.855,57.418,0 -2.27,57.03,0 -2.66,56.73,0 -3.32,56.44,0 -3.7,56.02,0 -3.38,55.99,0 -3.359,56.005,0 
				</coordinates>
			</LineString>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="ADDIKL00000000000001">
			<name>IKL pipeline (Ingolstadt–Kralupy–Litvínov) — TAL extension</name>
			<description><![CDATA[Classification: Crude oil pipeline — continuation of the TAL system (IKL: Ingolstadt–Kralupy–Litvínov)<br>Route: Vohburg/Ingolstadt (junction with TAL) → Czech border → Nelahozeves central tank farm near Kralupy, supplying the Kralupy and Litvínov refineries; 347 km<br>Owner/Operator: MERO ČR (Czech state pipeline company)<br>Capacity: ~200,000 b/d usable for the Czech Republic (~10 Mt/y design)<br>Status: Operational — since the TAL-PLUS expansion went live in 2025, TAL + IKL can deliver up to 8 Mt/y, covering the entire Czech crude demand<br>Recent data: In March 2025 the Czech Republic completed its switch away from Russian Druzhba deliveries; TAL-PLUS raised TAL throughput from 6,400 to 7,500 m³/hour<br>Strategic role: The western supply route that made Czech independence from Russian pipeline crude possible — Trieste → Alps → Ingolstadt → Prague region<br>Risks: Full dependence on the Trieste/TAL corridor now that Druzhba flows have ended; capacity sized close to national demand]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_icon?color=1976d2&amp;id=2000&amp;scale=450</styleUrl>
