		<Placemark>
			<name>TAL pipeline</name>
			<description>Trans Alpine Pipeline (TAL)
The Transalpine Pipeline (TAL) is one of Europe’s most important crude oil transportation systems. It transports imported crude oil from the Port of Trieste, Italy, across the Alps to refineries in Austria, Germany, and the Czech Republic.



Crude oil arrives at Trieste by tanker from producing regions including Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan, the Middle East, the North Sea, the United States, and Africa. After being unloaded at the Trieste Marine Terminal, the crude is pumped through the TAL pipeline network to inland storage facilities and refineries.



This section of the pipeline supplies the Bayernoil refining complex (Vohburg and Neustadt), helping provide transportation fuels and petrochemical feedstocks to southern Germany.



Route:
Global Crude Supply → Port of Trieste → TAL Pipeline → Lenting Tank Farm → Bayernoil Refinery (Vohburg / Neustadt)



Key Facts:
• Pipeline length: approximately 465 km
• Starting point: Trieste, Italy
• Main destination: Southern Germany, Austria, Czech Republic
• Transported product: Crude Oil
• Strategic role: Primary crude oil supply route for Central European refineries</description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_icon?color=1976d2&amp;id=2000&amp;scale=450</styleUrl>
