					53.61652943762361,23.82677165684339,0 55.73844495787689,24.23826558587521,0 56.35414850314482,25.1987654300518,0 
				</coordinates>
			</LineString>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Trans-Sakhalin Oil Pipeline — Sakhalin-2</name>
			<description>Sakhalin - 2 route

What is the Sakhalin-2 project?

Sakhalin Energy operates the Sakhalin-2 Project.

It is one of Russia’s largest integrated:

offshore oil,
offshore gas,
LNG export projects.
The project includes:

1. Offshore fields

Main offshore fields:

Piltun-Astokhskoye
Lunskoye
These fields produce:

crude oil,
natural gas.

2. Pipelines across Sakhalin Island

Hydrocarbons are transported southward across the island through pipelines.


3. Prigorodnoye LNG plant

At the south of the island:

gas is liquefied into LNG,
oil is exported by tanker.
This is where the cargo in your article was loaded.


What is Sakhalin Blend crude?

“Sakhalin Blend” is the crude oil exported from the Sakhalin-2 project.

It is:

light crude,
sweet crude (low sulfur),
attractive for Asian refiners.
The interesting point is that this oil is partly produced alongside LNG operations.

That is why sanctions exemptions exist:

if Japan stopped taking Sakhalin crude, it could disrupt the entire LNG chain feeding Japan.


Why is Japan still importing it?

Japan depends heavily on LNG imports for power generation.

The Sakhalin-2 Project supplies LNG directly to Japanese utilities because:

shipping distance is short,
supply is stable,
Japan already owns minority stakes through:
Mitsui &amp; Co.
Mitsubishi Corporation
So the US and G7 created a specific exemption allowing Japan to continue importing Sakhalin-related crude and LNG.</description>
