	<Folder>
		<name>Maritime routes</name>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Cold Lake Blend route</name>
			<description>Crude: Cold Lake Blend
API: ~19.5–20.0°
Sulfur: ~3.5–3.9%
Type: Heavy, sour diluted bitumen
Origin: Cold Lake oil-sands region, Alberta; produced mainly through in-situ steam recovery, blended with diluent and transported toward Edmonton and the Trans Mountain system
Markets: Historically Canada and the United States; growing exports to the U.S. West Coast and Asia through Westridge Marine Terminal. Rotterdam should be presented as a possible representative route rather than the grade’s primary regular destination.
Used for: Heavy fuel components, asphalt feedstock, diesel and other products in complex refineries equipped with cokers and desulfurization units
Pricing: Usually valued at a discount to WTI and Brent because of its high density, sulfur content and conversion costs; the discount varies with pipeline capacity, freight and heavy-crude demand
Vessels: Aframax tanker from Westridge; larger onward cargoes may require transshipment
Transit: Around 30–40 days to Rotterdam via the Pacific, Panama Canal, Atlantic, English Channel and Dover Strait
Risks: Pipeline congestion, diluent costs, wildfires and operational outages in Alberta, Vancouver loading limits, Panama delays, long-distance freight and dense Channel traffic</description>
