		<Placemark>
			<name>Saharan Blend route</name>
			<description>API: ~45° (light)
Sulfur: ~0.1% (very low)
Type: Light, sweet crude — a commingled export blend, not a single field.
Origin: Algeria; blended from Saharan fields (dominated by Hassi Messaoud, gathered at Haoud El Hamra) and exported through Skikda, Arzew or Bejaia terminals.
Markets: Mainly the Mediterranean and Northwest Europe, with additional sales to the Americas.
Used for: High light-distillate yield — naphtha, gasoline, jet fuel and diesel — plus petrochemical feed; its low sulphur means minimal desulphurisation cost, ideal for simpler and mid-complexity refineries.
Pricing: Monthly Sonatrach OSP set as a variable differential to Dated Brent, frequently at a premium.
Vessels: Usually Aframax; Suezmax for larger cargoes.
Transit: Around 2 days / ~450 nm from Skikda to Fos-sur-Mer across the western Mediterranean; ~5–6 days to Rotterdam via the Strait of Gibraltar.
Risks: Low — no major chokepoints; mainly Gulf of Lion mistral weather, port congestion and occasional Algerian loading or pipeline disruptions (Gibraltar transit only if routed to the Atlantic).</description>
			<styleUrl>#stylemap_id02</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
				<tessellate>1</tessellate>
				<coordinates>
					6.939508765107738,36.88880302234791,0 6.597759024239593,37.60688030029786,0 5.79435056388273,38.80280264287649,0 5.192549632927312,40.50242277568254,0 4.938327436476548,43.38064883167617,0 4.901126363949658,43.41450603818715,0 
				</coordinates>
			</LineString>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Es Sider route</name>
			<description>API: ~37° (light)
Sulfur: ~0.4% (sweet)
Type: Light, sweet crude — a commercial export blend named after its terminal, fed by several Sirte Basin fields.
Origin: Libya; gathered from Waha, Gialo and other Sirte Basin fields and exported through the Es Sider terminal via offshore Single Buoy Moorings (SBMs).
Markets: Mainly the Mediterranean and Northwest Europe (Italy, Spain, France, Germany, the Netherlands), with occasional sales to Asia.
Used for: High gasoline and middle-distillate yield with low sulphur; well suited to Mediterranean and mid-complexity refineries.
Pricing: Monthly NOC/Waha OSP set as a variable differential to Dated Brent, with a Libyan political-risk element.
Vessels: Usually Suezmax or Aframax, loaded offshore at the SBMs.
Transit: Around 5–6 days / ~1,300–1,450 nm from Es Sider to Fos-sur-Mer via the Strait of Sicily; ~7–9 days to Rotterdam via the Strait of Gibraltar.
Risks: Libyan political instability — field shutdowns, port blockades and force majeure at the Es Sider terminal, plus militia/security risk; Strait of Sicily traffic density en route.</description>
			<styleUrl>#stylemap_id2</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
				<tessellate>1</tessellate>
				<coordinates>
					18.35596912396328,30.68834646924192,0 13.54114224798351,35.22509704572018,0 13.3339340684015,36.43726026793413,0 8.117250326889776,38.11726405364553,0 4.935933745798977,43.42443173647109,0 
				</coordinates>
			</LineString>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Girassol route</name>
			<description>API: ~30° (medium)
Sulfur: ~0.34% (sweet)
Type: Medium, sweet crude — the commingled Girassol + Jasmim + Rosa stream processed on the Girassol FPSO.
Origin: Angola; produced in deepwater Block 17 and exported directly offshore from the FPSO via a CALM buoy — no onshore terminal or pipeline.
Markets: Mainly China (over half of Angolan exports) and India, with a material share to Europe (led by Spain and the Netherlands).
Used for: Good gasoil and middle-distillate yield with low sulphur; suits complex Northwest European and Asian cracking refineries.
Pricing: Variable differential to Dated Brent, in line with West African official selling prices.
Vessels: Suezmax to Europe; VLCC for the long-haul Asian trade — vessel size affects the discharge port, as a laden VLCC is draft-limited to the deepest terminals.
Transit: Around 20–24 days / ~6,400–6,900 nm from Block 17 up the Atlantic around West Africa to Lysekil; longer to Asia via the Cape of Good Hope.
Risks: Gulf of Guinea piracy and armed-robbery risk at the loading end; long Atlantic and North Sea weather exposure; VLCC draft limits at discharge. No Suez, Hormuz or Gibraltar transit.</description>
			<styleUrl>#stylemap_id24</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
				<tessellate>1</tessellate>
