		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Liza route</name>
			<description>API: ~32° (medium)
Sulfur: ~0.59% (sweet)
Type: Medium, sweet crude — a single-development stream from the Liza Destiny FPSO (distinct from Unity Gold and Payara Gold).
Origin: Guyana; produced offshore in the Stabroek Block and loaded directly from the FPSO by ship-to-ship transfer — no onshore terminal or pipeline.
Markets: Predominantly Europe (about two-thirds of Guyanese exports in 2024), with additional sales to the United States and Asia.
Used for: Strong middle-distillate, diesel and jet yield; low sulphur makes it a favoured IMO-compliant feed for complex European refineries.
Pricing: Variable differential to Dated Brent (the &quot;Latin Dated Brent&quot; strip), recently around +$1.30/bbl.
Vessels: Usually Suezmax; some Aframax, loaded offshore via tandem transfer.
Transit: Around 13–16 days / ~4,400–4,800 nm transatlantic from the Liza field to Lysekil via the English Channel (or north-about Scotland), North Sea and Skagerrak.
Risks: North Atlantic and North Sea weather, Dover Strait/Channel traffic density and the Skagerrak approach; offshore-loading weather windows. No piracy or chokepoint exposure on the route.</description>
			<styleUrl>#stylemap_id20</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
				<tessellate>1</tessellate>
				<coordinates>
					-56.9169407616409,8.017149440466609,0 -53.98962135433751,16.20685518031413,0 -35.64261635163013,39.94978219636562,0 -4.948882600512566,49.5367256147621,0 0.9926929166654497,50.74272144205962,0 4.131152803618104,51.94452678257312,0 
				</coordinates>
			</LineString>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Bonny light route</name>
			<description>Crude: Bonny Light
API: ~32.9°
Sulfur: ~0.16%
Type: Light, very sweet Nigerian crude
Origin: Niger Delta; exported FOB from the Bonny Terminal, Nigeria
Markets: Mainly Europe and Asia, including the Netherlands, France, India and China
Used for: Gasoline, diesel, gasoil, jet fuel and vacuum gasoil
Pricing: Usually priced at a premium or discount to Dated Brent; during the March–April 2026 supply crisis, Bonny Light reached premiums of roughly +$7.50 to above +$10/bbl
Vessels: Typically loaded in standard cargoes of about 950,000 barrels, generally on Suezmax tankers
Transit: Around 14–18 days from Bonny Terminal to Rotterdam
Risks: Pipeline theft and sabotage, loading disruptions, Niger Delta security, Gulf of Guinea piracy, Atlantic weather and congestion in the English Channel</description>
