	<Folder>
		<name>Major Industrial &amp; Energy Hubs</name>
		<Placemark id="0B1B82F80D3ED2D647F7">
			<name>Sasol Secunda Synthetic Fuels &amp; Petrochemical Complex</name>
			<description>Hub: Secunda Industrial &amp; Synthetic Fuels Complex
Classification: Major coal-to-liquids, gas-to-liquids and petrochemical hub
Location: Secunda, Mpumalanga Province, South Africa
Owner/Operator: Sasol
Main feedstocks: Coal from Sasol’s nearby mining operations and natural gas imported from Mozambique through the Mozambique–Secunda Pipeline
Main activities: Coal gasification, synthesis-gas production, Fischer–Tropsch conversion, fuel upgrading, chemical production and gas distribution
Main products: Synthetic gasoline, diesel, jet-fuel components, LPG, ethylene, propylene, solvents, waxes, polymers, fertilizers and other industrial chemicals
Fuel-production capacity: Commonly estimated at around 150,000–160,000 barrels per day of synthetic fuels and related products, although actual output varies with plant availability and feedstock supply.
Gas connection: Secunda is the South African endpoint of the approximately 865 km Mozambique–Secunda Pipeline, which transports natural gas from the Pande and Temane fields in Mozambique. The pipeline carries natural gas only, not crude oil.
Industrial integration: The complex combines fuel production, petrochemicals, utilities, storage, pipelines and downstream chemical manufacturing in one highly integrated site
Markets: South Africa’s domestic transport-fuel and industrial markets, with selected chemical and specialty-product exports
Strategic role: One of South Africa’s most important energy and chemical production centres, reducing reliance on imported crude oil and supplying a substantial share of domestic fuels and basic petrochemicals.
Energy-transition role: Sasol is studying increased use of natural gas, renewable electricity, green hydrogen, sustainable feedstocks and lower-carbon aviation fuels to progressively reduce the complex’s dependence on coal
Risks: Declining Mozambican gas availability, coal-supply constraints, very high greenhouse-gas emissions, carbon regulation, water and electricity shortages, plant outages and the high cost of decarbonising the site</description>
