	<Folder>
		<name>Offshore tanker loading terminal</name>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Bonny CLP / SPM Offshore Loading</name>
			<description>Asset type: Offshore tanker loading terminal (submarine pipeline + mooring buoys — no jetty or quay)
Country: Nigeria
Region: Rivers State, Gulf of Guinea, a few km off Bonny Island
Nearest settlement: Bonny Island
Latitude / Longitude: 4.1867°N, 7.2367°E (Crude Loading Platform); companion moorings at SPM1 4.1717°N/7.2283°E and SPM2 4.1733°N/7.2433°E
Coordinate confidence: Exact (three independent navigational sources agree)
Operator: Shell (SPDC/Renaissance)
Configuration: One CLP plus three SPMs; SPM1 and SPM2 load crude fed by submarine pipeline from the tank farm, SPM3 (further offshore, 4.11°N/7.125°E) handles discharge via a PLEM (pipeline end manifold)
Role in the supply chain: This is the actual loading point — the place a tanker moors, connects floating hoses, and takes on Bonny Light. Because the water close to Bonny Island is too shallow for a laden tanker to come alongside, loading happens here, offshore, rather than at the tank farm itself. Same mechanism as the Es Sider terminal in Libya: onshore storage, offshore buoy loading.
Typical vessel: Suezmax, some VLCC
Source: findaport.com Port of Bonny Offshore Terminal navigational register (CLP/SPM coordinates); ShipNext/port registries for terminal configuration</description>
